05-28}}</ref>\n*  ''Huffington Post'': Top 20 Trans Pioneer of 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/20/transgender-day-of-remembrance-2011_n_1101681.html#s475756&title=Thomas_Beatie |title=Transgender Day of Remembrance 2011: 20 Trans Pioneers, Thomas Beatie |publisher=huffingtonpost.com |date=2011-11-20 |accessdate=2013-05-28 |first=Noah |last=Michelson}}</ref>\n* Handsome Men (Who Were Born Female)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oddee.com/item_98038.aspx |title=10 Handsome Men (Who Were Born Female), Thomas Beatie |publisher=oddee.com |date=2012-01-18 |accessdate=2013-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ThomasBeatie.com The Official Thomas Beatie Website]\n*{{IMDb name|2976126}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beatie, Thomas}}\n[[Category:People from Oahu]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual men]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Transgender and transsexual writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Transgender rights activists]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:People from Bend, Oregon]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Welsh descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT American people of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Equivamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Beatie"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois", "text_new": "{{For|the state House election|2020 Illinois House of Representatives election}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois\n| country            = Illinois\n| type               = legislative\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois\n| previous_year      = 2018\n| next_election      = 2022 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois\n| next_year          = 2022\n| seats_for_election = All 18 Illinois seats to the [[United States House of Representatives]]\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| last_election1     = 13\n| seats1             = \n| seat_change1       = \n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| swing1             = \n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| last_election2     = 5\n| seats2             = \n| seat_change2       = \n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| swing2             = \n| map_image          = \n| map_caption        = \n}}\n{{Elections in Illinois}}\nThe '''2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect the 18 [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representatives]] from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Illinois]], one from each of the state's 18 [[Illinois's congressional districts|congressional districts]]. The elections will coincide with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2020|other elections]] to the House of Representatives, [[2020 United States Senate elections|elections]] to the [[United States Senate]] and various [[2020 United States elections#State elections|state]] and [[2020 United States elections#Local elections|local elections]].\n{{toclimit|2}}\n\n==District 1==\n{{see also|Illinois's 1st congressional district}}\nThe 1st district takes in the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]] of [[Chicago]], the southern suburbs of Chicago, and continues southwest to [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]]. The incumbent is Democrat [[Bobby Rush]], who was re-elected with 73.5% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\">{{cite web|last1=Wasserman|first1=David|last2=Flinn|first2=Ally|title=2018 House Popular Vote Tracker|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1WxDaxD5az6kdOjJncmGph37z0BPNhV1fNAH_g7IkpC0/htmlview|publisher=Cook Political Report|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Nominee=====\n*[[Bobby Rush]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref name=\"ILcand\"/>\n\n=====Eliminated in Primary=====\n*Robert Emmons Jr., nonprofit executive<ref>{{cite news|last1=McQueary|first1=Kristen|title=Column: Ignore Bobby Rush. Kim Foxx's wounds are self-inflicted.|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/mcqueary/ct-perspec-mcqueary-bobby-rush-kim-foxx-smollett-20190408-story.html|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 16, 2019}}</ref>\n*Sarah Gad, law student and opioid recovery advocate<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chicagodefender.com/chicago-activist-announces-run-for-u-s-congress-would-be-nations-first-formerly-incarcerated-woman-elected/|title=Chicago activist Sarah Gad could be nation's first formerly incarcerated women legislator|date=October 28, 2019|accessdate=November 23, 2019|publisher=[[The Chicago Defender]]}}</ref>\n*Ameena Matthews, community activist<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garmes |first1=Kyle |title=Matthews follows activism with run in First District |url=http://www.beverlyreview.net/news/community_news/article_a452c95a-a270-11e9-a03f-bbf661ab607d.html|accessdate=July 9, 2019 |publisher=The Beverly Review |date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\