 music|Country]]<ref name=\"PitchforkRev\"/>|[[pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/taylor-swift/biography|title=Taylor Swift Biography|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=October 13, 2019|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709093054/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/taylor-swift/biography|archivedate=October 13, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| length     = 40:28\n| label      = [[Big Machine Records|Big Machine]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Nathan Chapman (record producer)|Nathan Chapman]]|[[Robert Ellis Orrall]]}}\n| next_title = [[The Taylor Swift Holiday Collection]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Taylor Swift studio albums\n | type       = studio\n | prev_title = \n | prev_year  = \n | title      = Taylor Swift\n | year       = 2006\n | next_title = [[Fearless (Taylor Swift album)|Fearless]]\n | next_year  = 2008\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Taylor Swift\n | type        = Studio\n | single1     = [[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\n | single1date = June 19, 2006\n | single2     = [[Teardrops on My Guitar]]\n | single2date = February 19, 2007\n | single3     = [[Our Song (Taylor Swift song)|Our Song]]\n | single3date = September 9, 2007 \n | single4     = [[Picture to Burn]]\n | single4date = February 3, 2008\n | single5     = [[Should've Said No]]\n | single5date = May 18, 2008<ref>{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715213425/http://www.bigmachinelabelgroup.com/release/shouldve-said-single/|title=\"Should've Said No\" (Single) - Big Machine Label Group|date=July 15, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''''Taylor Swift''''' is the self-titled debut [[studio album]] by American singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]], released on October 24, 2006, by [[Big Machine Records]]. Swift was 16 years old at the time of the album's release and wrote its songs during her [[freshman year]] of high school. Swift has writing credits on all of the album's songs, including those co-written with [[Liz Rose]]. Swift experimented with several [[record producer|producers]], ultimately choosing [[Nathan Chapman (record producer)|Nathan Chapman]], who had produced her [[demo album]].''Taylor Swift'' is a [[Country music|country]] album, with some tracks having [[Pop music|pop]] and [[pop rock]] sensibilities. Lyrically, the album speaks of romantic relationships, a couple of which Swift wrote from observing them before being in one. It also touches on Swift's friends and her personal struggles in [[high school]]. \n\nFive singles were released from ''Taylor Swift''; all  reached the top 40 of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart and has been [[Music recording sales certification|certified platinum or multi-platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). Swift's debut single and the album's lead single \"[[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\" peaked at number six on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]] chart. \"[[Teardrops on My Guitar]]\" was the album's best-performing song on the Hot 100, spending 48 weeks on the chart and becoming Swift's first top 20 hit. The third single \"[[Our Song (Taylor Swift song)|Our Song]]\" made Swift the youngest person in history to single-handedly write and perform a number-one song on the Hot Country Songs chart; \"[[Picture to Burn]]\" peaked at number three on the chart, while \"[[Should've Said No]]\" became the second single from the album to top the chart. Swift promoted the album by performing as the opening act, for the tours by artists such as [[Rascal Flatts]], [[George Strait]], [[Brad Paisley]], [[Tim McGraw]] and [[Faith Hill]].\n\n''Taylor Swift'' received generally positive reviews from music critics, who praised Swift's talent at such a young age. The album enjoyed commercial success and launched Swift's career in country music. In the United States, it topped the [[Top Country Albums|''Billboard'' Top Country Albums]] Chart for 24 weeks, and was certified [[RIAA certifications|7\u00d7 platinum]] by the RIAA for selling over seven million copies. ''Taylor Swift'' was the longest-charting album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] of the 2000s decade, remaining on the chart for 275 weeks in total. The album was also certified gold in [[British Phonographic Industry|the United Kingdom]], and platinum in [[Australian Recording Industry Association|Australia]] and [[Music Canada|Canada]].\n\n==Background==\nSwift is from [[Reading, Pennsylvania]] and developed an early interest in [[country music]] and [[songwriting]].<ref name=\"allbio\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0000472102| tab=biography |pure_url=yes}}|title=Taylor Swift > Biography & History|publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[Macrovision Corporation]]|accessdate=February 1, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106150839/https://www.allmusic.com/artist/taylor-swift-mn0000472102/biography|archivedate=November 6, 2018|url-status=live|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine}}</ref> When she was eleven, she and her family made their first visit to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] in pursuit of a [[record deal]], though nothing came out of it.<ref name=\"albuminfo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1546980/when-she-thinks-tim-mcgraw-taylor-swift-savors-payoff.jhtml|title=When She Thinks \"Tim McGraw,\" Taylor Swift Savors Payoff: Hardworking Teen to Open for George Strait Next Year|date=December 1, 2006|first=Edward|last=Morris|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229194025/http://www.cmt.com/news/1546980/when-she-thinks-tim-mcgraw-taylor-swift-savors-payoff/|archivedate=December 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Swift was judged and neglected by [[record labels]] for being too young.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> In regards to the labels which rejected her, she said,\n{{quote|\"I can understand. They were afraid to put out a 13-year-old. They were afraid to put out a 14-year-old. Then they were afraid to put out a 15-year-old. Then they were nervous about putting out a 16-year-old. And I'm sure if I hadn't signed with [[Scott Borchetta]] [head of [[Big Machine Records]]], everybody would be afraid to put out a 17-year-old.\"<ref name=\"albuminfo\" />}}\n\n==Development and music==\n[[File:Taylor Swift.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A young female with curly blond hair faces down at an acoustic guitar made of koa wood while a large microphone is placed close to her. She is wearing patterned, red dress.|Swift performing \"[[Teardrops on My Guitar]]\". The song became the best-charting single from ''Taylor Swift'' on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].]]\n\nSwift wrote \"[[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\" during her freshman year, knowing that she and her [[High school|senior]] boyfriend, Brandon Borello, would break up at the end of the year when he left for college. Rose said Swift showed up at her after school job writing songs for [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing|Sony/ATV]] \"with the idea and the melody. She knew exactly what she wanted.\"<ref name=\"book\">{{cite book|last=Parvis|first=Sarah|title=Taylor Swift|publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing|isbn=978-0-7407-8596-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qeCvg-69Zp8C&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=%22that%27s+your+first+single%22+%22swift%22#v=onepage&q=&f=false|accessdate=February 20, 2010|date=September 15, 2009|via=[[Google Books]]|page=24}}</ref> The nostalgic song describes a summer romance and Swift's hope that when Borello \"think[s] [[Tim McGraw]]\" he would \"think [her] favorite song\" \u2013 McGraw's \"Can't Tell Me Nothin\" \u2013 and remember her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/20-questions/1574118/20-questions-with-taylor-swift.jhtml|title=20 Questions With Taylor Swift|date=November 12, 2007|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623085030/http://www.cmt.com/news/1574118/20-questions-with-taylor-swift/|archivedate=June 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Conversely, \"[[Picture to Burn]]\" describes a girl furious after a break-up. Swift says that while the song is about \"just being mad\" and is \"completely, brutally honest\"; she gave it a comedic edge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1583617/taylor-swift-fans-the-flames-on-picture-to-burn.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Fans the Flames on 'Picture to Burn'|first=Laura|last=Douglas|date=March 18, 2008|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811054811/http://www.cmt.com/news/1583617/taylor-swift-fans-the-flames-on-picture-to-burn/|archivedate=August 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> While at work after school, Swift \"found [her]self just sitting there with [her] guitar going, 'I hate his stupid truck that he doesn't let me drive. He's such a redneck! Oh my God!',\" a line which developed into the song's chorus.<ref name=\"gacblog\" /> The up-tempo song is heavy with [[banjo]]s and [[drums]], while the chorus is marked by distorted guitars and big vocals.<ref name=\"topabout\">{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/top10lists/tp/TaylorSwiftTop10Songs.htm|title=Top 10 Taylor Swift Songs|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010|first=Sean|last=Dooley|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121205072313/http://countrymusic.about.com/od/top10lists/tp/TaylorSwiftTop10Songs.htm|archivedate=December 5, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe singer penned the autobiographical song \"The Outside\" as an outlet at age twelve, the year she began writing her own songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gactv.com/gac/pac_ctnt/text/0,,GAC_26058_47131,00.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630045043/http://www.gactv.com/gac/pac_ctnt/text/0,,GAC_26058_47131,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 30, 2012|title=More About Taylor Swift|first=Jamison|last=Rotch|work=[[Great American Country]]|publisher=[[Scripps Networks Interactive]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> Like many of the other songs she wrote early on, the song describes the unhappiness and loneliness Swift felt when her love of country music alienated her from her peers.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427064615/http://www.gactv.com/gac/nw_music_beat/article/0,,GAC_26067_5087557,00.html|archive-date=April 27, 2015|url=http://www.gactv.com/gac/nw_music_beat/article/0,,GAC_26067_5087557,00.html|title=Taylor Swift Is a Veteran at 16|first=Ronna|last=Rubin|date=October 23, 2006|work=[[Great American Country]]|publisher=[[Scripps Networks Interactive]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> Swift wrote \"Tied Together with a Smile\" the day she learned one of her best friends was [[bulimic]], a fact which shocked her. She recalled, \"How can somebody that seems so strong have such a horrible, horrible weakness? Something that is killing her.\"<ref name=\"gacblog\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.gactv.com/gactv/asktheartist/taylorswift/|title=Ask the Artist|first=Taylor|last=Swift|work=[[Great American Country]]|publisher=[[Scripps Networks Interactive]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070708082423/http://blogs.gactv.com/gactv/asktheartist/taylorswift/|archivedate=July 8, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The lyrics to \"Tied Together with a Smile\" describe a beautiful girl trying to hide her inner turbulence and mourn that \"You're tied together with a smile/But you're coming undone\".<ref name=\"about.com\">{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/cdreviewsmz/fr/TaylorSwift.htm|title=Taylor Swift \u2013 'Taylor Swift'|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=January 26, 2010|first=Shelly|last=Fabian|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120524232809/http://countrymusic.about.com/od/cdreviewsmz/fr/TaylorSwift.htm|archivedate=May 24, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Swift commented, \"I always thought that one of the biggest overlooked problems American girls face is insecurity.\"<ref name=\"gacblog\" /> She wrote \"[[Should've Said No]]\" according to \"something really, really dramatic and crazy happening to [her] and [her] needing to address it in the form of music\".<ref name=\"catchingup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylors-time-catching-up-with-taylor-swift-20100125|page=2|title=Taylor's Time: Catching Up With Taylor Swift|date=January 25, 2010|accessdate=February 1, 2010|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Jann Wenner|first=Austin|last=Scaggs|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722213556/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/taylors-time-catching-up-with-taylor-swift-101783/|archivedate=July 22, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The song was a last minute addition to ''Taylor Swift'': Swift had written it two days before [[audio mastering|mastering]] was scheduled and booklets were about to be printed; she then called her producer and completed the song overnight.<ref name=\"catchingup\" />\n\n\"Mary's Song (Oh My My My)\" was actually inspired by her next-door neighbors' long lasting marriage, being the opposite of what [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloids]] fixate on.<ref name=\"about.com\" /> Swift wrote \"[[Our Song (Taylor Swift song)|Our Song]]\" for her freshman year of high school [[talent show]] with no intentions of including it on the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1585582/taylor-swift-shares-story-and-success-of-award-winning-our-song.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Shares Story and Success of Award-Winning 'Our Song'|first=Craig|last=Shelburne|date=April 15, 2008|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209195936/http://www.cmt.com/news/1585582/taylor-swift-shares-story-and-success-of-award-winning-our-song/|archivedate=February 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She claimed she \"just knew there was something about it\" and chose to include it on ''Taylor Swift''. \"I wrote it about this guy I was dating, and how we didn't have a song. So I went ahead and wrote us one.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gactv.com/gac/nw_headlines/article/0,3034,GAC_26063_5680314,00.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630045100/http://www.gactv.com/gac/nw_headlines/article/0,3034,GAC_26063_5680314,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 30, 2012|title=Taylor Swift Proves Her Staying Power|date=August 23, 2007|work=[[Great American Country]]|publisher=[[Scripps Networks Interactive]]|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> The song is a narrative and describes a young couple who use the events in their lives in place of a regular song. The banjo-riddled song is placed at the end of the album due to its closing lyrics, a request to \"play it again\".<ref name=\"about.com\" /> \"Invisible\" is ballad describing loneliness and heartache of going unnoticed. Sean Dooley of [[About.com]] writes, the \"[[piano]]-driven song [...] perfectly captures the awkward teenage angst we all endure\u2014or have endured\u2014at one time or another.\"<ref name=\"topabout\" />\n\n==Recording==\nWhile recording her [[demo album]], Swift worked with demo producer [[Nathan Chapman (record producer)|Nathan Chapman]], whom she met in a little shed behind a publishing company she was at.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> Swift said, \"I'd always go in there and play him some new songs, and the next week he would have this awesome track, on which he played every instrument, and it sounded like a record. We did this for a period of a year to two years before I got my record deal.\"<ref name=\"albuminfo\" />\n\nTo record ''Taylor Swift'', she had to choose which [[album producer]] she would work with: \"Then, all of a sudden, it was, 'OK, we're going to use this producer' or 'We're going to use that producer.'\"<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> After experimenting with different producers, originating from Nashville, Swift chose Chapman because of the unique sound he put into songs.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> Big Machine Records was skeptical about hiring Chapman because he had never done a studio album prior to ''Taylor Swift'', only demos.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> Swift described the songs he produced as \"the right chemistry hit[ting]\" and therefore, Big Machine Records accepted Chapman producing some of the album's songs.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> In the end, Chapman produced all but one of the tracks on ''Taylor Swift''.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> Recording was executed during a four-month period before 2005 was over.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" />\n\n==Packaging and release==\n''Taylor Swift'' was released on October 24, 2006 with eleven tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000I5YCCO|title=Taylor Swift: Taylor Swift: Music|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306003209/http://www.amazon.com/Taylor-Swift/dp/B000I5YCCO|archivedate=March 6, 2016|url-status=live|asin=B000I5YCCO}}</ref> Swift was highly involved in the album packaging, designing doodle graphics herself. She also personally capitalized specific letters in the lyrics from each song to spell out hidden messages,<ref name=\"liner\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Taylor Swift |others=Taylor Swift |year=2006 |type=booklet |publisher=Big Machine Records |id=BMR120702}}</ref> a feat she would also execute for her succeeding albums.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Fearless Platinum Edition|others=Taylor Swift|year=2008|type=CD|publisher=Big Machine Records|id=BMRATS0250}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Speak Now Target Exclusive|others=Taylor Swift|year=2010|type=CD|publisher=Big Machine Records|id=BTMSR0300B}}</ref> On November 6, 2007, the album was released under the title ''Taylor Swift Deluxe Edition'' for a limited time. The deluxe edition contained three new songs: \"I'm Only Me When I'm with You\", \"Invisible\" and \"A Perfectly Good Heart\", the radio edits for \"Teardrops on My Guitar\", and \"Our Song\", and Swift's first phone conversation with Tim McGraw. The release also bore new artwork and a bonus [[DVD]] with all of Swift's music videos at the time (\"Tim McGraw\", \"Teardrops on My Guitar\", and \"Our Song\"), behind-the-scenes footage of \"Teardrops on My Guitar\" and \"Our Song\" music videos, and a performance of \"Picture to Burn\", among other material.<ref name=\"deluxeamazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000YF86JS|title=Taylor Swift (Deluxe Edition) (CD+DVD): Taylor Swift: Music|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408024254/http://www.amazon.com/Taylor-Swift-Deluxe-Edition-DVD/dp/B000YF86JS|archivedate=April 8, 2016|url-status=live|asin=B000YF86JS}}</ref> The American retail company [[Target Corporation|Target]] released an exclusive version of ''Taylor Swift Deluxe Edition'', with performances of Swift during McGraw and Hill's [[Soul2Soul II Tour]].<ref name=\"deluxeamazon\"/> A third and final edition appeared on March 18, 2008 with the original album artwork, including the three new songs from the ''Taylor Swift Deluxe Edition'', as well as the radio edit of \"Picture to Burn,\" and an additional pop remix of \"Teardrops on My Guitar\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0014I4KH6|title=Taylor Swift: Taylor Swift:  Music|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303201617/http://www.amazon.com/Taylor-Swift/dp/B0014I4KH6|archivedate=March 3, 2016|url-status=live|asin=B0014I4KH6}}</ref> This version of the album was also released on vinyl in 2016. A [[karaoke]] version of ''Taylor Swift'' was released on January 27, 2009, containing the first fourteen tracks from the album on both [[CD+G]] and DVD.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B001NJY5Y4|title=Taylor Swift Karaoke (2-Disc Karaoke CDG & DVD): Taylor Swift: MP3 Downloads|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=August 1, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053225/http://www.amazon.com/Taylor-Swift-TAYLOR-SWIFT/dp/B001NJY5Y4|archivedate=March 4, 2016|url-status=live|asin=B001NJY5Y4}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n[[File:Swift, Taylor (2007).jpg|thumb|right|alt=A female teen with blond hair and blue eyes, clothed by a sparkly silver dress, faces forward and plays a koa wood guitar.|Swift performing \"[[Our Song (Taylor Swift song)|Our Song]]\" when opening for [[Rascal Flatts]]' Me and My Gang Tour. It was her first number-one on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Hot Country Songs]].]]\n\nSwift's first broadcast performance of \"Tim McGraw\" was on October 24, 2006 on ''[[Good Morning America]]''.<ref name=\"taylorjoinstour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1543489/taylor-swift-joins-rascal-flatts-tour.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Joins Rascal Flatts Tour|date=October 18, 2006|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623061511/http://www.cmt.com/news/1543489/taylor-swift-joins-rascal-flatts-tour/|archivedate=June 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Other songs from ''Taylor Swift'' have been performed on television programs, award shows, and festivals such as ''[[The Megan Mullally Show]]'',<ref name=\"taylorjoinstour\" /> the New Faces Show,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1547326/new-faces-show-performers-announced.jhtml|title=New Faces Show Performers Announced|date=December 5, 2006|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811054954/http://www.cmt.com/news/1547326/new-faces-show-performers-announced/|archivedate=August 11, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[America's Got Talent]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1567495/taylor-swift-will-sing-on-americas-got-talent.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Will Sing on America's Got Talent|date=August 20, 2007|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811054944/http://www.cmt.com/news/1567495/taylor-swift-will-sing-on-americas-got-talent/|archivedate=August 11, 2017}}</ref> [[Total Request Live]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/news/318549/trl-embraced-me-for-who-i-am.jhtml|title=Video: TRL Embraced Me for who I Am|publisher=[[MTV]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|date=November 16, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904191914/http://www.mtv.com/video-clips/mr98c3/trl-embraced-me-for-who-i-am|archivedate=September 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> the [[2008 CMT Music Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/misc/225276/picture-to-burn-from-the-2008-cmt-music-awards.jhtml|title=Video: Picture to Burn (From the 2008 CMT Music Awards)|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810210800/http://www.cmt.com/videos/misc/225276/picture-to-burn-from-the-2008-cmt-music-awards.jhtml|archivedate=August 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Academy of Country Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/taylor-swift/240043/shouldve-said-no-from-the-2008-acm-awards.jhtml|title=Video: Should've Said No (From the 2008 ACM Awards)|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080613225353/http://www.cmt.com/videos/taylor-swift/240043/shouldve-said-no-from-the-2008-acm-awards.jhtml|archivedate=June 13, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20201158,00.html|title=Taylor Swift Blogs About Her Wet Performance|date=May 19, 2008|first=Shelley|last=Akers|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Warner|Time Warner, Inc]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810212142/http://people.com/celebrity/taylor-swift-blogs-about-her-wet-performance/|archivedate=August 10, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Swift spent much of 2006 promoting \"Tim McGraw\" and ''Taylor Swift'' in a radio tour.<ref name=\"albuminfo\" /> In regards to the extensive radio tour, Swift commented, \"Radio tours for most artists last six weeks. Mine lasted six months. That's because I wanted it to. I wanted to meet every single one of the people that was helping me out.\"<ref name=\"albuminfo\" />\n\nSwift also promoted the album by performing as an opening act for several country artists' [[concert tour]]s. She opened for [[Rascal Flatts]] on several dates, from October 19 to November 3, 2006, included on the Me and My Gang Tour (2006\u201307), performing a total of five songs from the album.<ref name=\"taylorjoinstour\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/concertreviewsm1/a/RFConReview1106.htm|title=Rascal Flatts Concert Review \u2013 Air Canada {{sic|hide=y|Center}} \u2013 November 1, 2006: Taylor Swift Opens the Show|first=Bobbi|last=Smith|page=1|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120707115849/http://countrymusic.about.com/od/concertreviewsm1/a/RFConReview1106.htm|archivedate=July 7, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She also served as opening act on twenty dates for [[George Strait]]'s 2007 United States tour,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1546137/taylor-swift-joins-george-straits-2007-tour.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Joins George Straits 2007 Tour|date=November 17, 2006|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729171151/http://www.cmt.com/news/1546137/taylor-swift-joins-george-straits-2007-tour/|archivedate=July 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and selected dates for [[Brad Paisley]]'s Bonfires & Amplifiers Tour (2007\u201308); Swift served as an opening act during all 2007 legs of the tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1549598/brad-paisley-plans-tour-with-three-opening-acts.jhtml|title=Brad Paisley Plans Tour With Three Opening Acts|date=January 9, 2007|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120728001055/http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1549598/brad-paisley-plans-tour-with-three-opening-acts.jhtml|archivedate=July 28, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1555074/brad-paisley-announces-more-tour-dates.jhtml|title=Brad Paisley Announces More Tour Dates|date=March 19, 2007|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013093235/http://www.cmt.com/news/1555074/brad-paisley-announces-more-tour-dates/|archivedate=October 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> During mid-2007, Swift engaged as the opening act on several dates for [[Tim McGraw]]'s and [[Faith Hill]]'s joint tour, [[Soul2Soul II Tour]] (2006\u201307).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1561014/taylor-swift-joins-tim-mcgraw-faith-hill-on-tour.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Joins Tim McGraw, Faith Hill on Tour|date=June 1, 2007|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|publisher=[[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]]|accessdate=March 11, 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120525193624/http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1561014/taylor-swift-joins-tim-mcgraw-faith-hill-on-tour.jhtml|archivedate=May 25, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Swift again opened for Flatts for their Still Feels Good Tour in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/concertreviewsm1/a/RFlattsConc08.htm|title=Rascal Flatts & Taylor Swift in Concert \u2013 Sacramento, CA \u2013 April 10, 2008|first=Shelly|last=Fabian|work=[[About.com]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 22, 2010|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710221412/http://countrymusic.about.com/od/concertreviewsm1/a/RFlattsConc08.htm|archivedate=July 10, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In addition, Swift performed six songs from ''Taylor Swift'' on her first headlining tour, the [[Fearless Tour]] (2009\u201310).\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\" was released as the [[lead single]] from ''Taylor Swift'' on June 19, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r843574|pure_url=yes}}|title=Tim McGraw > Overview|work=Allmusic|publisher=Macrovision Corporation|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> The song was critically appreciated for Swift's delivery.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> \"Tim McGraw\" enjoyed commercial success, peaking at number forty on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and at number six on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Hot Country Songs]];<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=taylor swift|chart=all}}|title=Tim McGraw by Taylor Swift|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> it was certified [[RIAA certifications|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for the shipment of 2,000,000 copies.<ref name=\"riaas\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Taylor+Swift&ti=&lab=&genre=&format=Single&date_option=release&from=&to=&award=&type=&category=&adv=SEARCH#search_section|title=RIAA \u2013 Taylor Swift singles|work=RIAA.com|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Teardrops on My Guitar]]\" was released as the second single from ''Taylor Swift''. \"Teardrops on My Guitar\" received critical success for its memorable chorus and crossover potential, as well as commercial success by becoming the best-charting single from ''Taylor Swift'' on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, peaking at number thirteen.<ref name=\"about.comtear\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/taylorteardrops.htm|title=Taylor Swift \u2013 Teardrops on My Guitar|first=Bill|last=Lamb|work=About.com|publisher=The New York Times Company|accessdate=February 21, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69sM2PANu?url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/taylorteardrops.htm|archivedate=August 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"billboardtear\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=taylor swift|chart=all}}|title=Teardrops on My Guitar by Taylor Swift|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> It became Swift's first pop crossover hit, peaking at number eleven on the now-canceled [[Pop 100]] chart. The song was certified double platinum by the RIAA for the shipment of 3,000,000 copies.<ref name=\"riaas\" /> \"Teardrops on My Guitar\" peaked at number forty-five in Canada and at number fifty-one in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"billboardtear\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/I%20Can%20Transform%20Ya%20ft%20Lil%20Wayne|title=The Official Charts Company \u2013 Taylor Swift \u2013 Teardrops on My Guitar|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=February 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Our Song (Taylor Swift song)|Our Song]]\" was released as the third single from the album. The song was critically favored, being described as \"gem\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/new/55348/fearless.html|title=Fearless \u2013 Taylor Swift|first=Rob|last=Sheffield|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|publisher=Alpha Media Group|accessdate=February 21, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124213458/http://www.blender.com/guide/new/55348/fearless.html|archivedate=November 24, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"Our Song\" peaked at number sixteen on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was certified quadruple platinum by the RIAA;<ref name=\"riaas\" /> it also became Swift's first-number one on Hot Country Songs.<ref name=\"riaaour\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=taylor swift|chart=all}}|title=Our Song by Taylor Swift|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> The song peaked at number thirty on the [[Canadian Hot 100]], becoming the best-charting single from ''Taylor Swift'' in Canada.<ref name=\"riaaour\" />\n\n\"[[Picture to Burn]]\" was released as the fourth single from ''Taylor Swift''. \"Picture to Burn\" was appreciated by contemporary critics for lyrics reflecting feminism.<ref name=\"about.com\" /> It became a fourth consecutive top ten single for Swift on the United States' chart Hot Country Songs and was certified double platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"riaas\" /><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=taylor swift|chart=all}}|title=Picture to Burn by Taylor Swift|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Should've Said No]]\" was released as the fifth and final single from the album. In the United States, \"Should've Said No\" became Swift's second number-one on Hot Country Songs and was certified double platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"riaas\" /><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=taylor swift|chart=all}}|title=Should've Said No by Taylor Swift|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc|accessdate=January 24, 2010}}</ref> The song made its highest international peak in the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]], at number eighteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showitem.asp?interpret=Taylor+Swift&titel=Should%27ve+Said+No&cat=s|title=Taylor Swift \u2013 Should've Said No (Song)|work=charts.nz|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]]|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n|rev2      = ''[[Country Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"weekly\" />\n|rev3      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev3score = 6.7/10<ref name=\"PitchforkRev\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/taylor-swift-taylor-swift/|title=Taylor Swift: Taylor Swift Album Review|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Johnston|first=Maura|date=August 19, 2019|accessdate=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Taylor Swift'' received positive reviews from contemporary critics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/a-brief-history-of-musical-wunderkinds-lorde/|title=A Brief History of Musical Wunderkinds|last=St. Asaph|first=Katherine|date=June 21, 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> Jeff Tamarkin of [[AllMusic]] described Swift as \"a fresh, still girlish voice, full of hope and na\u00efvet\u00e9, but it's also a confident and mature one\". He said her \"talent to be reckoned\" was portrayed through the songs \"Tim McGraw\", \"The Outside\", and \"Mary's Song (Oh My My My)\". Tamarkin criticized producer [[Nathan Chapman (record producer)|Nathan Chapman]] for applying \"a gloss that not all [songs] really require and in some cases would do better to shed\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r860523|pure_url=yes}}|title=Taylor Swift > Review|work=AllMusic|accessdate=January 26, 2010|first=Jeff|last=Tamarkin}}</ref> Rick Bell of ''[[Country Standard Time]]'' gave a positive review, saying that Swift had \"smart songwriting\" and that \"her deeply personal, self-penned songs, particularly 'The Outside' and 'Our Song'\" were \"stirring\".<ref name=\"cst\">{{cite web|url=http://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/cdreview.asp?xid=3371|title=''Taylor Swift'' review|last=Bell|first=Rick|work=[[Country Standard Time]]|accessdate=March 31, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69sLzvlVh?url=http://www.countrystandardtime.com/d/cdreview.asp?xid=3371|archivedate=August 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He compared her sound to [[Cyndi Thomson]] and [[Hilary Duff]].<ref name=\"cst\" /> Chris Neal of ''[[Country Weekly]]'' said that Swift \"demonstrat[es] an honesty, intelligence and idealism with which listeners of any age will be able to connect\" and added that \"the more thoughtful material suggests a talent poised to last well past high school.\"<ref name=\"weekly\">{{cite web|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/taylor_swift/reviews/348|title=''Taylor Swift'' review|last=Neal|first=Chris|date=December 4, 2006|work=[[Country Weekly]]|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> Ken Rosenbaum of ''[[The Toledo Blade]]'' wrote Swift \"deftly handles lyrics and subjects in that shadowy area between teenager and womanhood.\"<ref name=\"blade\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7MwpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=swQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6414,3357467&dq=taylor-swift+album&hl=en|title=The Who's 1st disc in 24 years, 'Endless Wire,' is a mixed bag|last=Rosenbaum|first=Ken|date=November 12, 2006|work=[[The Toledo Blade]]|page=12|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Organization \n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\"| Ref\n|-\n| ! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"1\"| 2008\n| [[Academy of Country Music Awards]]\n| Album of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vrazel |first1=Jarrod |title=2008 Academy of Country Music Awards Winners |url=http://www.acountry.com/2008-academy-of-country-music-awards-winners/ |publisher=[[Academy of Country Music]] |accessdate=July 7, 2015 |date=May 19, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707172111/http://www.acountry.com/2008-academy-of-country-music-awards-winners/ |archivedate=July 7, 2015}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Commercial performance==\n[[File:Taylor Swift at Yahoo crop.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A blond female, clothed by a white sundress and large sunglasses, in a semi-right profile view playing a wooden acoustic guitar. Behind her appears a window in daylight.|Swift performing \"[[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\" in 2007.]]\nOn the week ending November 11, 2006, ''Taylor Swift'' debuted at number nineteen on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] due to sales of 40,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/56784/hannah-montana-trumps-my-chem-legend-at-no-1|title='Hannah Montana' Trumps My Chem, Legend At No. 1|last=Hasty|first=Katie|date=November 1, 2006|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://acharts.us/album/14694|title=Taylor Swift \u2013 Taylor Swift \u2013 Music Charts|publisher=aCharts.us|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> It reached its highest sales week on the week ending January 5, 2008 with 187,000 copies sold. After sixty-three weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200, on the week ending January 19, 2008, the album reached its charting peak at number five due to sales of 47,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1046867/radiohead-nudges-blige-from-atop-album-chart|title=Radiohead Nudges Blige From Atop Album Chart|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=January 9, 2008|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 21, 2010}}</ref> ''Taylor Swift'' marked the longest stay on the ''Billboard'' 200 by any album released in the decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/266889/chart-beat-thursday-taylor-swift-tim-mcgraw-linked-again|title=Chart Beat Thursday: Taylor Swift, Tim McGraw Linked Again|date=October 29, 2009|work=Billboard|accessdate=July 12, 2019|first=Gary|last=Trust}}</ref> The album stayed on the chart for 275 weeks in total.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6221976/taylor-swift-career-timeline-photo-gallery|title=Taylor Swift's Career Timeline: From 'Tim McGraw' to '1989'|date=November 4, 2014|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref> The album topped ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Top Country Albums]] Chart for twenty-four non-consecutive weeks.<ref name=\"countryus\"/> On the week ending August 2, 2008, Swift's EP ''[[Beautiful Eyes]]'' replaced ''Taylor Swift'' as the chart's number one album. With ''Taylor Swift'' charting at number two, Swift became the first artist to hold the first two positions on Top Country Albums since [[LeAnn Rimes]] charted in 1997 with ''[[Blue (LeAnn Rimes album)|Blue]]'' (1996) and ''[[Unchained Melody: The Early Years]]'' (1997).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1591603/taylor-swift-bumps-herself-out-of-no-1-slot.jhtml|title=Taylor Swift Bumps Herself Out of No. 1 Slot|date=July 26, 2008|work=[[CMT News]]|accessdate=January 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countrystandardtime.com/news/newsitem.asp?xid=1947|title=Taylor Swift owns top of country chart|date=July 23, 2008|accessdate=January 9, 2010|work=[[Great American Country]]|publisher=Scripps Networks Interactive}}</ref> The lead single \"Tim McGraw\" stayed on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 for twenty weeks, peaking at number 40, and also reached number 6 on the Hot Country Songs chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/6221976/taylor-swift-career-timeline-photo-gallery|title=Taylor Swift's Career Timeline: From 'Tim McGraw' to '1989'|author=Billboard Staff|magazine=Billboard|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> As of July 2019, the album has sold 5.72 million pure copies in the United States.<ref name=\"USJuly2019\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8519784/taylor-swift-career-sales-streaming-totals-2019-ask-billboard|first=Gary|last=Trust|title=Ask Billboard: Taylor Swift's Career Sales & Streaming Totals, From 'Tim McGraw' to 'You Need to Calm Down'|magazine=Billboard|date=July 14, 2019|accessdate=July 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715081725/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8519784/taylor-swift-career-sales-streaming-totals-2019-ask-billboard|archive-date=July 15, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As of December 2017, ''Taylor Swift'' is certified [[RIAA certification|7\u00d7 Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], for earning over seven million units in the country.<ref name=\"mostawarded\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bigmachinerecords.com/index.cfm?id=6&viewStory=369|title=Taylor Swift's Fearless is Most Awarded Album in Country Music History|date=March 18, 2010|work=[[Big Machine Records]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115082527/http://www.bigmachinerecords.com/index.cfm?id=6&viewStory=369|archivedate=November 15, 2010|accessdate=March 20, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n\nSix years after its release, ''Taylor Swift'' debuted at number thirty-eight on the [[New Zealand Albums Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=1881 |title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart &#124; The Official New Zealand Music Chart |publisher=Nztop40.co.nz |date=March 19, 2012 |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> ''Taylor Swift'' peaked at number fourteen on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"BillboardCanada\"/> and was [[Music recording sales certifications|certified double platinum]] by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA).<ref name=\"cria\"/> In Australia, ''Taylor Swift'' peaked at number thirty-three on the main chart and at number three on the country-genre chart.<ref name=\"auschart\"/><ref name=\"aria\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_country.asp?chart=1F20|title=Top 20 Country Chart|work=ARIAcharts.com.au|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|date=March 14, 2009|accessdate=February 20, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5oGK8wG4e?url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_country.asp?chart=1F20|archivedate=March 16, 2010|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On the week ending September 5, 2009, it entered the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number 88; the following week, it reached its peak at number 81.<ref name=\"uk\" /> The album has been certified Gold by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI) for sales of more than 100,000 copies.<ref name=\"bpi\" />\n{{clear}}\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the album's [[liner notes]]<ref name=\"liner\" />\n\nAll tracks are produced by [[Nathan Chapman (record producer)|Nathan Chapman]], except where noted.\n{{Track listing\n| headline = ''Taylor Swift'' {{nobold|\u2013 Standard edition}}<ref name=itunes>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/taylor-swift-bonus-track-version/id275621626|title=Taylor Swift (Bonus Track Version)|work=[[iTunes Store]]|publisher=[[Apple, Inc.|Apple, Inc]]|accessdate=October 24, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Taylor-Swift/dp/B0014I4KH6/|title=Taylor Swift: Taylor Swift|publisher=[[Amazon.com]] (US) Amazon.com Inc|accessdate=January 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| total_length = 40:28\n\n| title1 = [[Tim McGraw (song)|Tim McGraw]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Taylor Swift]]|[[Liz Rose]]}}\n| length1 = 3:54\n\n| title2 = [[Picture to Burn]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Swift|Rose}}\n| length2 = 2:55\n\n| title3 = [[Teardrops on My Guitar]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Swift|Rose}}\n| length3 = 3:35\n\n| title4 = A Place in This World\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Swift|Rose|[[Robert Ellis Orrall]]|[[Angelo Petraglia|Angelo]]}}\n| length4 = 3:22\n\n| title5 = Cold as You\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Swift|Rose}}\n| length5 = 4:0