isation and the Web 2.0|journal=Ethics and Information Technology|volume=10|pages=41\u201356|year=2008|last1=Parsell|first1=Mitch}}\n* Preece, J. (2000). ''Online Communities: Supporting Sociability, Designing Usability.'' Chichester: John Wiley & Sons Ltd. ({{ISBN|0-471-80599-8}})\n* {{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/111293835/Prodnik-Jernej-Post-Fordist-Communities-and-Cyberspace-A-Critical-Approach |title=Post-Fordist Communities and Cyberspace, A Critical Approach |author=Prodnik, Jernej (2012) |date= |work=In H. Breslow and A. Mousoutzanis (eds.), Cybercultures: Mediations of Community, Culture, Politics|pages= 75\u2013100 |publisher=Rodopi: Amsterdam, New York |accessdate=2 February 2013}}\n* [[Howard Rheingold|Rheingold, H.]] (2000). ''The Virtual Community: Homesteading on the Electronic Frontier.'' London: MIT Press. ({{ISBN|0-262-68121-8}})\n** The author has made available an [http://www.rheingold.com/vc/book/intro.html online copy]\n* {{cite web |url=http://inderscience.metapress.com/link.asp?id=j2888h3537761355 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103202659/http://inderscience.metapress.com/link.asp?id=j2888h3537761355 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-03 |title=? |author=Rosenkranz, C., Feddersen, C. (2010) |date= 2017-12-14|work=Managing viable virtual communities: an exploratory case study and explanatory model |page=Volume 6, Number 1 5\u201314 |publisher=International Journal of Web Based Communities }}\n* [[John Seabrook|Seabrook, J.]] 1997. ''Deeper: My Two-Year Odyssey in Cyberspace'' Simon & Schuster ({{ISBN|0-684-80175-2}})\n*Smith, M. [https://web.archive.org/web/20060903180302/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/soc/csoc/papers/voices/Voices.htm \"Voices from the WELL: The Logic of the Virtual Commons\"] UCLA Department of Sociology.\n* Sudweeks, F., McLaughlin, M.L. & [[Sheizaf Rafaeli|Rafaeli, S.]] (1998) ''Network and Netplay Virtual Groups on the Internet'', MIT Press.\n** Portions available online as: [http://jcmc.indiana.edu/vol2/issue4/ Journal of Computer Mediated Communication, 2]\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.vandercrabben.com/?p=30|title=Performed Intimacy in Virtual Worlds|author=Van der Crabben, Jan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531092715/http://www.vandercrabben.com/?p=30|archive-date=31 May 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* Barry Wellman, \"An Electronic Group is Virtually a Social Network.\" Pp.&nbsp;179\u2013205 in ''Culture of the Internet'', edited by Sara Kiesler. Mahwah, NJ: Lawrence Erlbaum, 1997. [https://web.archive.org/web/19981203140803/http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/%7Ewellman/ Translated into German as \"Die elektronische Gruppe als soziales Netzwerk.\" Pp. 134\u201367 in ''Virtuelle Gruppen'', edited by Udo Thiedeke. Wiesbaden: Westdeutscher Verlag, 2000.]\n* Trier, M. (2007) ''Virtual Knowledge Communities \u2013 IT-supported Visualization and Analysis''. Saarbr\u00fccken, Germany: [[VDM Publishing|VDM Verlag Dr. M\u00fcller]]. ({{ISBN|3-8364-1540-2}}).\n* Urstadt, Bryant, \"Social Networking Is Not a Business: Web 2.0\u2014the dream of the user-built, user-centered, user-run Internet\u2014has delivered on just about every promise except profit. Will its most prominent example, social networking, ever make any money?\", [[Technology Review|MIT Technology Review]], July/August 2008\n\n<!-- READ THIS FIRST:\nDo not add HTML links to this article to promote your site. Instead of free advertising, what you do is vandalism, stealing and abuse -- the same thing you don't want people doing to your site. Read [[Wikipedia:External links]] to find out what links are OK. HTML links added here will likely result in its speedy deletion.\n-->\n\n{{Online social networking}}\n{{Social networking}}\n{{BBS}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Virtual reality]]\n[[Category:Community building]]\n[[Category:Social information processing]]\n[[Category:Community websites| ]]\n[[Category:Social software]]\n[[Category:Virtual communities| ]]\n", "name_user": "Stonecoil", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed wording of first sentence under PURPOSE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virtual_community"}
{"title_page": "End-user license agreement", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=November 2010}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2008}}\n}}\nAn '''end-user license agreement''' ('''EULA''') is a legal contract entered into between a [[software developer]] or vendor and the user of the [[software]], often where the software has been purchased by the user from an intermediary such as a retailer. A EULA specifies in detail the rights and restrictions which apply to the use of the software.<ref>[[Linux Foundation]], [http://www.linfo.org/eula.html EULA Definition], published 28 February 2006, accessed 10 August 2019</ref>\n\nMany form contracts are only contained in digital form, and only presented to a user as a [[#Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses|click-through]] which the user must \"accept\". As the user may not see the agreement until after he or she has already purchased the software, these documents may be [[contracts of adhesion]].\n\nSoftware companies often make special agreements with large businesses and government entities that include support contracts and specially drafted warranties.\n\nSome end-user license agreements accompany shrink-wrapped software that is presented to a user sometimes on paper or more usually electronically, during the installation procedure. The user has the choice of accepting or rejecting the agreement. The installation of the software is conditional to the user clicking a button labelled \"accept\".  See <!--the # (called an \"anchor\") means it is on the same page-->[[#Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses|below]].\n\nMany EULAs assert extensive liability limitations.  Most commonly, an EULA will attempt to [[hold harmless]] the software licensor in the event that the software causes damage to the user's computer or data, but some software also proposes limitations on whether the licensor can be held liable for damage that arises through improper use of the software (for example, incorrectly using tax preparation software and incurring penalties as a result). One case upholding such limitations on [[consequential damages]] is ''M.A. Mortenson Co. v. Timberline Software Corp., et al.''{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Some EULAs also claim restrictions on venue and applicable law in the event that a legal dispute arises.\n\nSome copyright owners use EULAs in an effort to circumvent limitations the applicable copyright law places on their copyrights (such as the limitations in sections 107\u2013122 of the [[United States Copyright Act]]), or to expand the scope of control over the work into areas for which copyright protection is denied by law (such as attempting to charge for, regulate or prevent private performances of a work beyond a certain number of performances or beyond a certain period of time). Such EULAs are, in essence, efforts to gain control, by contract, over matters upon which copyright law precludes control. \n<ref name=moglen>{{cite web\n|title=Enforcing the GNU GPL\n|url=https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/enforcing-gpl.html\n|work=gnu.org\n|publisher=[[Free Software Foundation]], Inc.\n|accessdate=20 May 2013\n|author=Eben Moglen\n|authorlink=Eben Moglen\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426151337/http://www.gnu.org/philosophy/enforcing-gpl.html\n|archivedate=26 April 2013\n|date=10 September 2001\n}}</ref> \nThis kind of EULAs concurs in aim with [[Digital rights management|DRM]] and both may be used as alternate methods for widening control over software.\n\nIn disputes of this nature in the United States, cases are often appealed and different circuit courts of appeal sometimes disagree about these clauses.  This provides an opportunity for the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] to intervene, which it has usually done in a scope-limited and cautious manner, providing little in the way of [[precedent]] or settled law. {{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nEnd-user license agreements are usually lengthy, and written in highly specific legal language, making it difficult for the average user to give informed consent.<ref>Bashir, M., Hayes, C., Lambert, A. D., & Kesan, J. P. (2015). Online privacy and informed consent: The dilemma of information asymmetry. Proceedings of the Association for Information Science and Technology, 52(1), 1-10. doi:10.1002/pra2.2015.145052010043</ref> If the company designs the end-user license agreement in a way that intentionally discourages users from reading them, and uses difficult to understand language, many of the users may not be giving informed consent.\n\n==Comparison with free software licenses==\n{{main|Free software license}}\nA [[free software]] license grants users of that software the rights to use for any purpose, modify and redistribute creative works and software, both of which are forbidden by the defaults of copyright, and generally not granted with [[proprietary software]]. These licenses typically include a disclaimer of [[warranty]], but this feature is not unique to free software.\n<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=A Comparison of the GPL and the Microsoft EULA\n|date=5 May 2003\n|pages=3, 12\u201316\n|url=http://asyd.net/docs/misc/comparing_the_gpl_to_eula.pdf\n|accessdate=19 July 2013\n|author=Con Zymaris\n|format=PDF\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006164013/http://www.asyd.net/docs/misc/comparing_the_gpl_to_eula.pdf\n|archivedate=6 October 2008\n}}</ref>\n[[Copyleft]] licenses also include a key addition provision that must be followed in order to copy or modify the software, that requires the user to provide source code for the work and to distribute their modifications under the same license (or sometimes a compatible one); thus effectively protecting derivative works from losing the original permissions and being used in proprietary programs.\n\nUnlike EULAs, free software licenses do not work as contractual extensions to existing legislation. No agreement between parties is ever held, because a copyright license is simply a declaration of permissions on something that otherwise would be disallowed by default under copyright law.<ref name=moglen />\n\n==Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses {{Anchor|Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses}}==\n{{main|Clickwrap|Browsewrap|Shrink wrap contract}}\n\nThe term '''shrink-wrap license''' refers colloquially to any software license agreement which is enclosed within a software package and is inaccessible to the customer until after purchase.  Typically, the license agreement is printed on paper included inside the boxed software.  It may also be presented to the user on-screen during installation, in which case the license is sometimes referred to as a '''click-wrap license'''.  The inability of the customer to review the license agreement before purchasing the software has caused such licenses to run afoul of legal challenges in some cases.\n\nWhether shrink-wrap licenses are legally binding differs between jurisdictions, though a majority of jurisdictions hold such licenses to be enforceable. At particular issue is the difference in opinion between two US courts in ''[http://www.internetlibrary.com/cases/lib_case209.cfm Klocek v. Gateway]'' and ''[http://www.netlitigation.com/netlitigation/cases/brower.htm Brower v. Gateway]''.  Both cases involved a shrink-wrapped license document provided by the online vendor of a computer system.  The terms of the shrink-wrapped license were not provided at the time of purchase, but were rather included with the shipped product as a printed document.  The license required the customer to return the product within a limited time frame if the license was not agreed to. In ''Brower'', New York's state appeals court ruled that the terms of the shrink-wrapped license document were enforceable because the customer's assent was evident by its failure to return the merchandise within the 30 days specified by the document.  The U.S. District Court of Kansas in ''Klocek'' ruled that the contract of sale was complete at the time of the transaction, and the additional shipped terms contained in a document similar to that in ''Brower'' did not constitute a contract, because the customer never agreed to them when the contract of sale was completed.\n\nFurther, in ''[[ProCD v. Zeidenberg]]'', the license was ruled enforceable because it was necessary for the customer to assent to the terms of the agreement by clicking on an \"I Agree\" button in order to install the software. In [[Specht v. Netscape Communications Corp.]], however, the licensee was able to download and install the software without first being required to review and positively assent to the terms of the agreement, and so the license was held to be unenforceable.\n\nClick-wrap license agreements refer to website based contract formation (see iLan Systems, Inc. v. Netscout Service Level Corp.). A common example of this occurs where a user must affirmatively assent to license terms of a website, by ''clicking'' \"yes\" on a pop-up, in order to access website features. This is therefore analogous to shrink-wrap licenses, where a buyer implied agrees to license terms by first removing the software package's shrink-wrap and then utilizing the software itself. In both types of analysis, focus is on the actions of end user and asks whether there is an explicit or implicit acceptance of the additional licensing terms.\n\n==Product liability==\nMost licenses for software sold at retail disclaim (as far as local laws permit) any [[warranty]] on the performance of the software and limit liability for any damages to the purchase price of the software.  One well-known case which upheld such a disclaimer is Mortenson v. Timberline .\n\n==Patent==\n{{main|Software patent}}\nIn addition to the implied [[exhaustion doctrine]], the distributor may include patent licenses along with software.\n\n==Reverse engineering==\nForms often prohibit users from [[reverse engineering]]. This may also serve to make it difficult to develop third-party software which interoperates with the licensed software, thus [[Vendor lock-in|increasing the value of the publisher's solutions]] through decreased customer choice. In the United States, EULA provisions can preempt the reverse engineering rights implied by fair use, c.f. [[Bowers v. Baystate Technologies]].\n\nSome licenses<ref>Examples include [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms994405.aspx Microsoft .NET Framework redistributable EULA]</ref> purport to prohibit a user's right to release data on the performance of the software, but this has yet to be challenged in court.\n\n==Enforceability of EULAs in the United States==\n{{Primary sources|section about the legal enforceability of end-user license agreement|date=July 2015}}\n\nThe enforceability of an EULA depends on several factors, one of them being the court in which the case is heard.  Some courts that have addressed the validity of the shrinkwrap license agreements have found some EULAs to be invalid, characterizing them as [[adhesion contract|contracts of adhesion]], [[Unconscionability|unconscionable]], and/or unacceptable pursuant to the [[Uniform Commercial Code|U.C.C.]]\u2014see, for instance, ''[[Step-Saver Data Systems, Inc. v. Wyse Technology]]'',<ref>939 F.2d 91 (3rd Cir., 1991)</ref> ''[[Vault Corp. v. Quaid Software Ltd.]]''.<ref>847 F.2d 255 (5th Cir., 1988)</ref>  Other courts have determined that the shrinkwrap license agreement is valid and enforceable: see ''[[ProCD, Inc. v. Zeidenberg]]'',<ref>86 F.3d 1447 (7th Cir., 1996)</ref> ''[[Microsoft Corp. v. Harmony Comps. & Elecs., Inc.|Microsoft v. Harmony Computers]]'',<ref>846 F. Supp. 208 (E.D.N.Y., 1994)</ref> ''Novell v. Network Trade Center'',<ref>25 F.Supp.2d 1218 (D. Utah, 1997)</ref> and ''[[Ariz. Cartridge Remanufacturers Ass'n v. Lexmark Int'l, Inc.]]''<ref>421 F.3d 981 (9th Cir., 2005)</ref> may have some bearing as well. No court has ruled on the validity of EULAs generally; decisions are limited to particular provisions and terms.\n\nThe [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|7th Circuit]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|8th Circuit]] subscribe to the \"licensed and not sold\" argument, while most other circuits do not {{Citation needed|date=September 2007}}.  In addition, the contracts' enforceability depends on whether the state has passed the [[Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act]] (UCITA) or Anti-UCITA]] ([[UCITA Bomb Shelter) laws. In Anti-UCITA states, the [[Uniform Commercial Code]] (UCC) has been amended to either specifically define software as a good (thus making it fall under the UCC), or to disallow contracts which specify that the terms of contract are subject to the laws of a state that has passed UCITA.\n\nRecently{{when|date=December 2013}}, publishers have begun to [[encryption|encrypt]] their software packages to make it impossible for a user to install the software without either agreeing to the license agreement or violating the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] (DMCA) and [[WIPO Copyright Treaty|foreign counterparts]].{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nThe DMCA specifically provides for reverse engineering of software for interoperability purposes, so there was some controversy as to whether software license agreement clauses which restrict this are enforceable.  The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|8th Circuit]] case of ''Davidson & Associates v. Jung''<ref>422 F. 3d 630 (8th Cir., 2005)</ref> determined that such clauses are enforceable, following the [[Federal Circuit]] decision of ''[[Bowers v. Baystate Technologies|Baystate v. Bowers]]''.<ref>302 F.3d 1334 (Fed. Cir., 2002)</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[Jerry Pournelle]] wrote in 1983, \"I've seen no evidence to show that ... Levitical agreements \u2014 full of \"Thou Shalt Nots\" \u2014 have any effect on piracy\". He gave an example of an EULA that was impossible for a user to comply with, stating \"Come on, fellows. No one expects these agreements to be kept\". Noting that in practice many companies were more generous to their customers than their EULAs required, Pournelle wondered \"Why, then, do they insist on making their customers sign 'agreements' that the customer has no intention of keeping, and which the company ''knows'' won't be kept? ... Must we continue making hypocrites out of both publishers and customers?\"<ref name=\"pournelle198306\">{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1983-06/1983_06_BYTE_08-06_16-Bit_Designs#page/n411/mode/2up | title=Zenith Z-100, Epson QX-10, Software Licensing, and the Software Piracy Problem | magazine=BYTE | date=June 1983 | accessdate=20 October 2013 | author=Pournelle, Jerry | pages=411}}</ref>\n\nOne common criticism of end-user license agreements is that they are often far too lengthy for users to devote the time to thoroughly read them. In March 2012, the [[PayPal]] end-user license agreement was 36,275 words long<ref>{{cite web|title=No One Reads the \"Terms And Conditions\" and Here\u2019s Why|url=http://1025kiss.com/no-one-reads-the-terms-and-conditions-and-heres-why/|publisher=102.5 KISSFM|accessdate=24 November 2012|author=Heathen|date=23 March 2012}}</ref> and in May 2011 the [[iTunes]] agreement was 56 pages long.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pidaparthy|first=Umika|title=What you should know about iTunes' 56-page legal terms|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/TECH/web/05/06/itunes.terms/|accessdate=24 November 2012|newspaper=CNN|date=May 6, 2011}}</ref> News sources reporting these findings asserted that the vast majority of users do not read the documents because of their length.\n\nSeveral companies have parodied this belief that users do not read the end-user-license agreements by adding unusual clauses, knowing that few users will ever read them. As an [[April Fool's Day]] joke, [[Gamestation]] added a clause stating that users who placed an order on April 1, 2010 agreed to irrevocably [[Deal with the Devil|give their soul]] to the company, which 7,500 users agreed to. Although there was a checkbox to exempt out of the \"immortal soul\" clause, few users checked it and thus Gamestation concluded that 88% of their users did not read the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|title=7,500 Online Shoppers Unknowingly Sold Their Souls|url=http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2010/04/15/online-shoppers-unknowingly-sold-souls/|accessdate=24 November 2012|newspaper=FoxNews.com|date=April 15, 2010}}</ref> The program ''PC Pitstop'' included a clause in their end-user license agreement stating that anybody who read the clause and contacted the company would receive a monetary reward, but it took four months and over 3,000 software downloads before anybody collected it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Magid|first=Larry|title=PC Pitstop|url=http://www.pcpitstop.com/spycheck/eula.asp|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref> During the installation of version 4 of the Advanced Query Tool the installer measured the elapsed time between the appearance and the acceptance of the end-user license agreements to calculate the average reading speed. If the agreements were accepted fast enough a dialog window \u201ccongratulated\u201d the users to their absurdly high reading speed of several hundred words per second.<ref>{{cite web|last=Willmott|first=Don|title=Backspace (v22n08)|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,1034132,00.asp|work=PCMag.com|accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref> ''[[South Park]]'' parodied this in the episode \"[[HumancentiPad]]\", where [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] had neglected to read the terms of service for his last iTunes update and therefore inadvertently agreed to have [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] employees experiment upon him.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Grady|first=Jason D.|title=South Park parodies iTunes terms and conditions|url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/apple/south-park-parodies-itunes-terms-and-conditions/10043|work=ZDNet|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nEnd-user license agreements have also been criticized for containing terms that impose onerous obligations on consumers. For example, Clickwrapped, a service that rates consumer companies according to how well they respect the rights of users, reports that they increasingly include a term that prevents a user from suing the company in court.<ref>Jamillah Knowles. ''Clickwrapped report tells you which sites claim ownership of your content, and you\u2019ll be surprised''. TheNextWeb. August 21, 2012. Accessed July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn a recent article published by Kevin Litman-Navarro for the New York Times, titled ''We Read 150 Privacy Policies. They Were an Incomprehensible Disaster''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/12/opinion/facebook-google-privacy-policies.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/12/opinion/facebook-google-privacy-policies.html|title=Opinion {{!}} We Read 150 Privacy Policies. They Were an Incomprehensible Disaster.|last=Litman-Navarro|first=Kevin|date=2019-06-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, the complexity of 150 terms from popular sites like Facebook, Airbnb, etc. were analyzed and comprehended. As a result, for example, the majority of licenses require college or higher-level degrees: \"To be successful in college, people need to understand texts with a score of 1300. People in the professions, like doctors and lawyers, should be able to understand materials with scores of 1440, while ninth graders should understand texts that score above 1050 to be on track for college or a career by the time they graduate. Many privacy policies exceed these standards.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abandonware]]\n* [[Clickwrap|Clickwrap license]]\n* [[Free software license]]\n* [[:wikt:Appendix:Glossary of legal terms in technology|Glossary of legal terms in technology]]\n** [[Good faith (law)]]\n**[[Contra proferentem]]\n* [[Index of Articles Relating to Terms of Service and Privacy Policies]]\n* [[License manager]]\n* [[List of software licenses]]\n* [[Shrink wrap contract]]\n* [[Software Asset Management]]\n* [[Software license]]\n* [[Terms of service]]\n* ''[[Vernor v. Autodesk, Inc.]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.frictionlessinsight.com/archives/2002/03/you-may-read-th.html Accessible editorial on enforcability of various EULA-type licenses in the United States from 2002..]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:End-user license agreement}}\n[[Category:Terms of service]]\n[[Category:Software licenses]]\n[[Category:Contract law]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Globalize|article|USA|2name=the United States|date=November 2010}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2008}}\n}}\nAn '''end-user license agreement''' ('''EULA''') is a legal contract entered into between a [[software developer]] or vendor and the user of the [[software]], often where the software has been purchased by the user from an intermediary such as a retailer. A EULA specifies in detail the rights and restrictions which apply to the use of the software.<ref>[[Linux Foundation]], [http://www.linfo.org/eula.html EULA Definition], published 28 February 2006, accessed 10 August 2019</ref>\n\nMany form contracts are only contained in digital form, and only presented to a user as a [[#Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses|click-through]] which the user must \"accept\". As the user may not see the agreement until after he or she has already purchased the software, these documents may be [[contracts of adhesion]].\n\nSoftware companies often make special agreements with large businesses and government entities that include support contracts and specially drafted warranties.\n\nSome end-user license agreements accompany shrink-wrapped software that is presented to a user sometimes on paper or more usually electronically, during the installation procedure. The user has the choice of accepting or rejecting the agreement. The installation of the software is conditional to the user clicking a button labelled \"accept\".  See <!--the # (called an \"anchor\") means it is on the same page-->[[#Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses|below]].\n\nMany EULAs assert extensive liability limitations.  Most commonly, an EULA will attempt to [[hold harmless]] the software licensor in the event that the software causes damage to the user's computer or data, but some software also proposes limitations on whether the licensor can be held liable for damage that arises through improper use of the software (for example, incorrectly using tax preparation software and incurring penalties as a result). One case upholding such limitations on [[consequential damages]] is ''M.A. Mortenson Co. v. Timberline Software Corp., et al.''{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Some EULAs also claim restrictions on venue and applicable law in the event that a legal dispute arises.\n\nSome copyright owners use EULAs in an effort to circumvent limitations the applicable copyright law places on their copyrights (such as the limitations in sections 107\u2013122 of the [[United States Copyright Act]]), or to expand the scope of control over the work into areas for which copyright protection is denied by law (such as attempting to charge for, regulate or prevent private performances of a work beyond a certain number of performances or beyond a certain period of time). Such EULAs are, in essence, efforts to gain control, by contract, over matters upon which copyright law precludes control. \n<ref name=moglen>{{cite web\n|title=Enforcing the GNU GPL\n|url=https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/enforcing-gpl.html\n|work=gnu.org\n|publisher=[[Free Software Foundation]], Inc.\n|accessdate=20 May 2013\n|author=Eben Moglen\n|authorlink=Eben Moglen\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130426151337/http://www.gnu.org/philosophy/enforcing-gpl.html\n|archivedate=26 April 2013\n|date=10 September 2001\n}}</ref> \nThis kind of EULAs concurs in aim with [[Digital rights management|DRM]] and both may be used as alternate methods for widening control over software.\n\nIn disputes of this nature in the United States, cases are often appealed and different circuit courts of appeal sometimes disagree about these clauses.  This provides an opportunity for the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] to intervene, which it has usually done in a scope-limited and cautious manner, providing little in the way of [[precedent]] or settled law. {{Citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nEnd-user license agreements are usually lengthy, and written in highly specific legal language, making it difficult for the average user to give informed consent.<ref>Bashir, M., Hayes, C., Lambert, A. D., & Kesan, J. P. (2015). Online privacy and informed consent: The dilemma of information asymmetry. Proceedings of the Association for Information Science and Technology, 52(1), 1-10. doi:10.1002/pra2.2015.145052010043</ref> If the company designs the end-user license agreement in a way that intentionally discourages users from reading them, and uses difficult to understand language, many of the users may not be giving informed consent.\n\n==Comparison with free software licenses==\n{{main|Free software license}}\nA [[free software]] license grants users of that software the rights to use for any purpose, modify and redistribute creative works and software, both of which are forbidden by the defaults of copyright, and generally not granted with [[proprietary software]]. These licenses typically include a disclaimer of [[warranty]], but this feature is not unique to free software.\n<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=A Comparison of the GPL and the Microsoft EULA\n|date=5 May 2003\n|pages=3, 12\u201316\n|url=http://asyd.net/docs/misc/comparing_the_gpl_to_eula.pdf\n|accessdate=19 July 2013\n|author=Con Zymaris\n|format=PDF\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006164013/http://www.asyd.net/docs/misc/comparing_the_gpl_to_eula.pdf\n|archivedate=6 October 2008\n}}</ref>\n[[Copyleft]] licenses also include a key addition provision that must be followed in order to copy or modify the software, that requires the user to provide source code for the work and to distribute their modifications under the same license (or sometimes a compatible one); thus effectively protecting derivative works from losing the original permissions and being used in proprietary programs.\n\nUnlike EULAs, free software licenses do not work as contractual extensions to existing legislation. No agreement between parties is ever held, because a copyright license is simply a declaration of permissions on something that otherwise would be disallowed by default under copyright law.<ref name=moglen />\n\n==Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses {{Anchor|Shrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses}}==\n{{main|Clickwrap|Browsewrap|Shrink wrap contract}}\n\nThe term '''shrink-wrap license''' refers colloquially to any software license agreement which is enclosed within a software package and is inaccessible to the customer until after purchase.  Typically, the license agreement is printed on paper included inside the boxed software.  It may also be presented to the user on-screen during installation, in which case the license is sometimes referred to as a '''click-wrap license'''.  The inability of the customer to review the license agreement before purchasing the software has caused such licenses to run afoul of legal challenges in some cases.\n\nWhether shrink-wrap licenses are legally binding differs between jurisdictions, though a majority of jurisdictions hold such licenses to be enforceable. At particular issue is the difference in opinion between two US courts in ''[http://www.internetlibrary.com/cases/lib_case209.cfm Klocek v. Gateway]'' and ''[http://www.netlitigation.com/netlitigation/cases/brower.htm Brower v. Gateway]''.  Both cases involved a shrink-wrapped license document provided by the online vendor of a computer system.  The terms of the shrink-wrapped license were not provided at the time of purchase, but were rather included with the shipped product as a printed document.  The license required the customer to return the product within a limited time frame if the license was not agreed to.  In ''Brower'', New York's state appeals court ruled that the terms of the shrink-wrapped license document were enforceable because the customer's assent was evident by its failure to return the merchandise within the 30 days specified by the document.  The U.S. District Court of Kansas in ''Klocek'' ruled that the contract of sale was complete at the time of the transaction, and the additional shipped terms contained in a document similar to that in ''Brower'' did not constitute a contract, because the customer never agreed to them when the contract of sale was completed.\n\nFurther, in ''[[ProCD v. Zeidenberg]]'', the license was ruled enforceable because it was necessary for the customer to assent to the terms of the agreement by clicking on an \"I Agree\" button in order to install the software. In [[Specht v. Netscape Communications Corp.]], however, the licensee was able to download and install the software without first being required to review and positively assent to the terms of the agreement, and so the license was held to be unenforceable.\n\nClick-wrap license agreements refer to website based contract formation (see iLan Systems, Inc. v. Netscout Service Level Corp.). A common example of this occurs where a user must affirmatively assent to license terms of a website, by ''clicking'' \"yes\" on a pop-up, in order to access website features. This is therefore analogous to shrink-wrap licenses, where a buyer implied agrees to license terms by first removing the software package's shrink-wrap and then utilizing the software itself. In both types of analysis, focus is on the actions of end user and asks whether there is an explicit or implicit acceptance of the additional licensing terms.\n\n==Product liability==\nMost licenses for software sold at retail disclaim (as far as local laws permit) any [[warranty]] on the performance of the software and limit liability for any damages to the purchase price of the software.  One well-known case which upheld such a disclaimer is Mortenson v. Timberline .\n\n==Patent==\n{{main|Software patent}}\nIn addition to the implied [[exhaustion doctrine]], the distributor may include patent licenses along with software.\n\n==Reverse engineering==\nForms often prohibit users from [[reverse engineering]]. This may also serve to make it difficult to develop third-party software which interoperates with the licensed software, thus [[Vendor lock-in|increasing the value of the publisher's solutions]] through decreased customer choice. In the United States, EULA provisions can preempt the reverse engineering rights implied by fair use, c.f. [[Bowers v. Baystate Technologies]].\n\nSome licenses<ref>Examples include [http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms994405.aspx Microsoft .NET Framework redistributable EULA]</ref> purport to prohibit a user's right to release data on the performance of the software, but this has yet to be challenged in court.\n\n==Enforceability of EULAs in the United States==\n{{Primary sources|section about the legal enforceability of end-user license agreement|date=July 2015}}\n\nThe enforceability of an EULA depends on several factors, one of them being the court in which the case is heard.  Some courts that have addressed the validity of the shrinkwrap license agreements have found some EULAs to be invalid, characterizing them as [[adhesion contract|contracts of adhesion]], [[Unconscionability|unconscionable]], and/or unacceptable pursuant to the [[Uniform Commercial Code|U.C.C.]]\u2014see, for instance, ''[[Step-Saver Data Systems, Inc. v. Wyse Technology]]'',<ref>939 F.2d 91 (3rd Cir., 1991)</ref> ''[[Vault Corp. v. Quaid Software Ltd.]]''.<ref>847 F.2d 255 (5th Cir., 1988)</ref>  Other courts have determined that the shrinkwrap license agreement is valid and enforceable: see ''[[ProCD, Inc. v. Zeidenberg]]'',<ref>86 F.3d 1447 (7th Cir., 1996)</ref> ''[[Microsoft Corp. v. Harmony Comps. & Elecs., Inc.|Microsoft v. Harmony Computers]]'',<ref>846 F. Supp. 208 (E.D.N.Y., 1994)</ref> ''Novell v. Network Trade Center'',<ref>25 F.Supp.2d 1218 (D. Utah, 1997)</ref> and ''[[Ariz. Cartridge Remanufacturers Ass'n v. Lexmark Int'l, Inc.]]''<ref>421 F.3d 981 (9th Cir., 2005)</ref> may have some bearing as well. No court has ruled on the validity of EULAs generally; decisions are limited to particular provisions and terms.\n\nThe [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|7th Circuit]] and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|8th Circuit]] subscribe to the \"licensed and not sold\" argument, while most other circuits do not {{Citation needed|date=September 2007}}.  In addition, the contracts' enforceability depends on whether the state has passed the [[Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act]] (UCITA) or Anti-UCITA]] ([[UCITA Bomb Shelter) laws. In Anti-UCITA states, the [[Uniform Commercial Code]] (UCC) has been amended to either specifically define software as a good (thus making it fall under the UCC), or to disallow contracts which specify that the terms of contract are subject to the laws of a state that has passed UCITA.\n\nRecently{{when|date=December 2013}}, publishers have begun to [[encryption|encrypt]] their software packages to make it impossible for a user to install the software without either agreeing to the license agreement or violating the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]] (DMCA) and [[WIPO Copyright Treaty|foreign counterparts]].{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nThe DMCA specifically provides for reverse engineering of software for interoperability purposes, so there was some controversy as to whether software license agreement clauses which restrict this are enforceable.  The [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit|8th Circuit]] case of ''Davidson & Associates v. Jung''<ref>422 F. 3d 630 (8th Cir., 2005)</ref> determined that such clauses are enforceable, following the [[Federal Circuit]] decision of ''[[Bowers v. Baystate Technologies|Baystate v. Bowers]]''.<ref>302 F.3d 1334 (Fed. Cir., 2002)</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n[[Jerry Pournelle]] wrote in 1983, \"I've seen no evidence to show that ... Levitical agreements \u2014 full of \"Thou Shalt Nots\" \u2014 have any effect on piracy\". He gave an example of an EULA that was impossible for a user to comply with, stating \"Come on, fellows. No one expects these agreements to be kept\". Noting that in practice many companies were more generous to their customers than their EULAs required, Pournelle wondered \"Why, then, do they insist on making their customers sign 'agreements' that the customer has no intention of keeping, and which the company ''knows'' won't be kept? ... Must we continue making hypocrites out of both publishers and customers?\"<ref name=\"pournelle198306\">{{cite magazine | url=https://archive.org/stream/byte-magazine-1983-06/1983_06_BYTE_08-06_16-Bit_Designs#page/n411/mode/2up | title=Zenith Z-100, Epson QX-10, Software Licensing, and the Software Piracy Problem | magazine=BYTE | date=June 1983 | accessdate=20 October 2013 | author=Pournelle, Jerry | pages=411}}</ref>\n\nOne common criticism of end-user license agreements is that they are often far too lengthy for users to devote the time to thoroughly read them. In March 2012, the [[PayPal]] end-user license agreement was 36,275 words long<ref>{{cite web|title=No One Reads the \"Terms And Conditions\" and Here\u2019s Why|url=http://1025kiss.com/no-one-reads-the-terms-and-conditions-and-heres-why/|publisher=102.5 KISSFM|accessdate=24 November 2012|author=Heathen|date=23 March 2012}}</ref> and in May 2011 the [[iTunes]] agreement was 56 pages long.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pidaparthy|first=Umika|title=What you should know about iTunes' 56-page legal terms|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/TECH/web/05/06/itunes.terms/|accessdate=24 November 2012|newspaper=CNN|date=May 6, 2011}}</ref> News sources reporting these findings asserted that the vast majority of users do not read the documents because of their length.\n\nSeveral companies have parodied this belief that users do not read the end-user-license agreements by adding unusual clauses, knowing that few users will ever read them. As an [[April Fool's Day]] joke, [[Gamestation]] added a clause stating that users who placed an order on April 1, 2010 agreed to irrevocably [[Deal with the Devil|give their soul]] to the company, which 7,500 users agreed to. Although there was a checkbox to exempt out of the \"immortal soul\" clause, few users checked it and thus Gamestation concluded that 88% of their users did not read the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|title=7,500 Online Shoppers Unknowingly Sold Their Souls|url=http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2010/04/15/online-shoppers-unknowingly-sold-souls/|accessdate=24 November 2012|newspaper=FoxNews.com|date=April 15, 2010}}</ref> The program ''PC Pitstop'' included a clause in their end-user license agreement stating that anybody who read the clause and contacted the company would receive a monetary reward, but it took four months and over 3,000 software downloads before anybody collected it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Magid|first=Larry|title=PC Pitstop|url=http://www.pcpitstop.com/spycheck/eula.asp|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref> During the installation of version 4 of the Advanced Query Tool the installer measured the elapsed time between the appearance and the acceptance of the end-user license agreements to calculate the average reading speed. If the agreements were accepted fast enough a dialog window \u201ccongratulated\u201d the users to their absurdly high reading speed of several hundred words per second.<ref>{{cite web|last=Willmott|first=Don|title=Backspace (v22n08)|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,1034132,00.asp|work=PCMag.com|accessdate=8 June 2013}}</ref> ''[[South Park]]'' parodied this in the episode \"[[HumancentiPad]]\", where [[Kyle Broflovski|Kyle]] had neglected to read the terms of service for his last iTunes update and therefore inadvertently agreed to have [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] employees experiment upon him.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Grady|first=Jason D.|title=South Park parodies iTunes terms and conditions|url=http://www.zdnet.com/blog/apple/south-park-parodies-itunes-terms-and-conditions/10043|work=ZDNet|accessdate=24 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nEnd-user license agreements have also been criticized for containing terms that impose onerous obligations on consumers. For example, Clickwrapped, a service that rates consumer companies according to how well they respect the rights of users, reports that they increasingly include a term that prevents a user from suing the company in court.<ref>Jamillah Knowles. ''Clickwrapped report tells you which sites claim ownership of your content, and you\u2019ll be surprised''. TheNextWeb. August 21, 2012. Accessed July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn a recent article published by Kevin Litman-Navarro for the New York Times, titled ''We Read 150 Privacy Policies. They Were an Incomprehensible Disaster''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/12/opinion/facebook-google-privacy-policies.html,%20https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/06/12/opinion/facebook-google-privacy-policies.html|title=Opinion {{!}} We Read 150 Privacy Policies. They Were an Incomprehensible Disaster.|last=Litman-Navarro|first=Kevin|date=2019-06-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-23|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, the complexity of 150 terms from popular sites like Facebook, Airbnb, etc. were analyzed and comprehended. As a result, for example, the majority of licenses require college or higher-level degrees: \"To be successful in college, people need to understand texts with a score of 1300. People in the professions, like doctors and lawyers, should be able to understand materials with scores of 1440, while ninth graders should understand texts that score above 1050 to be on track for college or a career by the time they graduate. Many privacy policies exceed these standards.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abandonware]]\n* [[Clickwrap|Clickwrap license]]\n* [[Free software license]]\n* [[:wikt:Appendix:Glossary of legal terms in technology|Glossary of legal terms in technology]]\n** [[Good faith (law)]]\n**[[Contra proferentem]]\n* [[Index of Articles Relating to Terms of Service and Privacy Policies]]\n* [[License manager]]\n* [[List of software licenses]]\n* [[Shrink wrap contract]]\n* [[Software Asset Management]]\n* [[Software license]]\n* [[Terms of service]]\n* ''[[Vernor v. Autodesk, Inc.]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.frictionlessinsight.com/archives/2002/03/you-may-read-th.html Accessible editorial on enforcability of various EULA-type licenses in the United States from 2002..]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:End-user license agreement}}\n[[Category:Terms of service]]\n[[Category:Software licenses]]\n[[Category:Contract law]]\n", "name_user": "Boxzoleil", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eShrink-wrap and click-wrap licenses:there was 2 spaces after a period so i just removed one of them :)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/End-user_license_agreement"}
{"title_page": "Todd Hido", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Todd Hido\n| image         = Todd Hido by McCall - CC.jpg\n| caption       = Todd Hido, Montana, 2019\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kent, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| education     = [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] \u2013 [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] <br/> [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] \u2013 [[California College of the Arts]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| website       = {{URL|www.toddhido.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Todd Hido''' (born 25 August 1968)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/prc/prcpov/artists/a16.html|title=Todd Hido|website=Bu.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> is an American [[contemporary artist]] and photographer.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-03|title=Todd Hido|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/todd-hido/|website=www.artnet.com}}</ref> He has produced 17 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/oct/02/unseen-photo-fair-amsterdam-review|title=A window on weird: step inside the Unseen Photo fair in Amsterdam|first=Sean|last=O'Hagan|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> had his work exhibited widely and included in various public collections.<ref>https://www.mmoca.org/learn/teachers/teaching-pages/todd-hido</ref>\n\n== Life and work ==\nHido was born August 25, 1968, in [[Kent, Ohio]], and graduated from [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Kent, Ohio)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kent City Schools Hall of Fame archives|url=https://www.kentschools.net/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-archives/ |year=2009 |work=KentSchools.net |publisher=Kent City School District |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> He graduated in 1991 with a B.F.A. from [[Tufts University]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=December 3, 2018 |title=Todd Hido: Sources and Influences \u2013 Aperture Foundation NY|url=https://aperture.org/workshops-classes/hido-2015/|newspaper=Aperture Foundation NY}}</ref> in [[Medford, Massachusetts]] and [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]. Between 1991 and 1992 he studied at [[Rhode Island School of Design]], [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"hido-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddhido.com/|title=Todd Hido|website=Toddhido.com|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1996 he gained an M.F.A. from [[California College of Arts and Crafts]], [[Oakland, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/academics/graduate/alumni|title=Graduate Alumni \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently based in [[San Francisco]], much of Hido's earlier work involves photographs of urban and suburban housing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designobserver.com/feature/exposure-suburban-house-at-night-by-todd-hido/39120/|title=Exposure: Surburban house at night, photographed by Todd Hido.|website=Designobserver.com |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> across the U.S.. He then started to include figures, mostly [[female nude]]s in interiors, and also to depict rural [[landscape]]s. In 2018, he released ''Bright Black World'', his first work photographed outside the U.S. with environmental overtones.\n\nHido says he is influenced by [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Edward Hopper]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Robert Adams (photographer)|Robert Adams]], [[Walker Evans]], [[Nan Goldin]], [[Emmet Gowin]], [[Larry Sultan]], [[Alfred Stieglitz]], [[Andreas Gursky]] and [[Rineke Dijkstra]]. Commissioned by Italian brand [[Bottega Veneta]], he photographed actress [[Lauren Hutton]] as well as models [[Joan Smalls]] and [[Vittoria Ceretti]] for the brand's spring/summer 2017 advertisements.<ref>Alexandra Venison (January 16, 2017), [http://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/fashion/the-news/lauren-hutton-stars-in-the-bottega-veneta-springsummer2017-campaign Lauren Hutton Stars In The Bottega Veneta Spring/Summer 2017 Campaign] ''Harper's Bazaar Arabia''.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Publications by Hido ===\n* ''House Hunting''.\n** Portland, OR: [[Nazraeli Press]], 2001. {{ISBN|978-3923922963}}.\n** Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2007. {{ISBN|978-1590051931}}.\n* ''Outskirts''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1590050286}}. Text by [[Luc Sante]]. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Taft Street''. One Picture Book 6. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1590050170}}.\n* ''Roaming''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1590050958}} Edition of 3000 copies.\n* ''Between the Two''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1590051764}}. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Crooked Cracked Tree in Fog''. One Picture Book 60. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-292-1}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Ohio.'' TBW Subscription Series #2. Oakland, CA: TBW, 2009. {{ASIN|B0087G1LD4}}. Edition of 800 copies. The other volumes are by Abner Nolan, Marianne Mueller and [[Alec Soth]].\n* ''A Road Divided''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1590052662}}.\n* ''Nymph Daughters''. Kamakura: Super Labo, 2010. {{ISBN|9784905052012}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1590053683}}\n* ''Todd Hido on Landscapes, Interiors, and the Nude.'' The Photography Workshop Series. New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-297-0}}. With an introduction by [[Gregory Halpern]].\n* ''B-Sides \u2013 Silver Meadows.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2014. {{ASIN|B00KP206DO}}. Edition of 500 copies. 50 individual cards in a clear plexi box, similar to a pack of playing cards.\n* ''Khrystyna's World.'' Amsterdam: Reflex Amsterdam, 2015. {{ISBN|978-90-71848-22-3}}. Edition of 500 copies. Published on the occasion of the exhibition, ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey: Khrystyna\u2019s World,'' September\u2013November 2015, Reflex Amsterdam, Amsterdam. With an essay by Katya Tylevich, \"Khrystyna's World: Detention in the Getaway Car\".<ref group=\"n\">A PDF of the book can be viewed [http://reflexamsterdam.com/wp-content/themes/newfish/pdf/todd-hido-khrystinas-world.pdf here within the Reflex Gallery website].</ref>\n* ''Seasons Road''. One Picture Book 93. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-456-7}}. Edition of 500 copies. 7 colour plates and 1 photographic print. \"Every year at Christmas for the past ten years, Todd Hido has traveled to Ohio to visit his parents. During his annual trip home, Hido makes photographs along the small road that serves as the namesake for this book.\"<ref>[http://www.nazraeli.com/opb/todd-hido-one-picture-book-93-seasons-road \"Todd Hido | One Picture Book #93 : Seasons Road\"] Nazraeli Press. Accessed 5 October 2016</ref>\n* ''Intimate Distance: Twenty-five Years of Photographs, A Chronological Album.'' New York: Aperture, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-360-1}}. With an essay by [[David Campany]].\n* ''B-Sides Box Sets \u2013 Homing In.'' Oakland, CA: B-Sides Box Sets, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5323-5128-0}}. Edition of 2000 copies. 50 individual cards in a box. Previously unpublished photographs from ''House Hunting.''\n* ''Bright Black World.'' Paso Robles, CA: Nazraeli Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1590054758}}. Text by Alexander Nemerov.\n\n=== Smaller publications by Hido ===\n* ''Collage Number Three.'' Deadbeat Club #41. Los Angeles, CA: Deadbeat Club, 2016.  Edition of 500 copies. 8 page zine which folds out to form a poster.\n* ''The Perfect Copy Vol. 1.'' San Francisco, CA: Colpa Press, 2016. Six 4-color [[Risograph]] photographic prints in screen printed envelope. Edition of 100 copies.\n\n=== Publications edited or with contributions by Hido ===\n* ''Witness No. 7''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052440}}. Photographs by Hido and [[Leon Borensztein]], and photographs of images from books by various people that have inspired Hido.\n* ''Cracked Trees''. One Picture Book 59. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052914}}. Photographs by Hido, paintings by 3rd grade students. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Motel Club.'' Nazraeli Press Six by Six, set 1 v. 4. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|1590052978}}. Edition of 100 copies. The other volumes are by [[Anthony Hernandez (photographer)|Anthony Hernandez]], [[Raymond Meeks]], [[Martin Parr]], [[Toshio Shibata]] and [[Mark Steinmetz]].\n* ''Alec Soth's Lonely Boy Mag 2: Boys and Their Cars.'' St. Paul, MN: [[Alec Soth|Little Brown Mushroom]], 2011. Edition of 1000 copies. Text and photographs by Todd Hido, [[Alec Soth]], Chad States and erotic [[diorama]]s by Peter Davidson.\n* ''One Day \u2013 10 Photographers.'' Heidelberg: [[Kehrer Verlag|Kehrer]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}. A boxed set of ten books of photographs taken on 21 June 2010. Edited by [[Harvey Benge]], each book by one photographer including Todd Hido, Jessica Backhaus, [[Gerry Badger]], Harvey Benge, [[John Gossage]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Rob Hornstra]], [[Rinko Kawauchi]], Eva Maria Ocherbauer and Martin Parr.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day \u2013 Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Here.'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-0-0}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''Leon Borensztein: American Portraits 1979\u20131989.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-305-8}}. Photographs by Leon Borensztein. Edited by Hido.\n* ''About Face'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-1-7}}. Exhibition guide\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-3-1}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''About Face.'' San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-2-4}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies. With forewords by Christopher McCall, and [[Richard Avedon]] (from ''In the American West''), an introduction by [[Philip Gefter]], and texts by [[Sandra S. Phillips]], and Ulrike Schneider.\n* ''The Open Road: Photography & the American Road Trip''. Edited and with text by [[David Campany]], photographs by Hido, [[Robert Frank]], [[Ed Ruscha]], [[Inge Morath]], [[Garry Winogrand]], [[William Egglestone]], [[Lee Friedlander]], [[Joel Meyerowitz]], [[Jacob Holdt]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Bernard Plossu]], [[Victor Burgin]], [[Joel Sternfeld]], [[Shin'ya Fujiwara]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Ryan McGinley]], [[Justine Kurland]], and Taiyo Onorato and Nico Krebs.\n** New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-240-6}}.\n** ''Road Trips: Voyages photographiques \u00e0 travers l\u2019Am\u00e9rique.'' Paris: Textuel, 2014. {{ISBN|9782845975002}}. French-language version.\n** ''En la Carretera: Viajes fotogr\u00e1ficos a trav\u00e9s de Norteam\u00e9rica.'' Madrid: La F\u00e1brica, 2014. {{ISBN|9788415691822}}. Spanish-language version.\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2015. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-4-8}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo ===\n{{BLP sources section|date=December 2018}}\n* 1997: SF Camerawork, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1998: ''House Hunting'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1999: Inman Gallery, Houston TX.\n* 2000: ''Photographs Taken at Night,'' Kohn Turner Gallery, Los Angeles, CA. Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.\n* 2000: ''Homing In,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2001: ''New Photographs,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX.\n* 2002: The [[Cleveland Museum of Art]], Cleveland, Ohio.\n* 2002: ''Open House,'' [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]].<ref>http://www.brucesilverstein.com/artists/todd-hido/biography</ref>\n* 2002: ''Roaming'', Paul Morris Gallery, New York, NY. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Taft Street, 3A Garage, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2003: Baldwin Gallery, Aspen Colorado. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL.\n* 2004: ''Roaming-New Landscapes'', Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EEDB153BF93BA35753C1A9629C8B63 |author=Glueck, Grace|title=Art in Review : Todd Hido \u2013 'Roaming: New Landscapes'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 8, 2004}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''Roaming'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Michael Berger Gallery, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Baldwin Gallery, Aspen, Colorado.\n* 2005 Todd Hido, Sheppard Gallery, University of Nevada, Reno, NV. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX. Karyn Lovegrove Gallery, Los Angeles, CA.\n* 2006: ''Unfinished Narratives'', Photographic Center Northwest, Seattle, WA.\n* 2007: ''Between the Two'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2007: Todd Hido, Rose Gallery, Santa Monica, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space15twenty.com/todd_hidos_a_road_divided |title=Space 15 Twenty |publisher=Space 15 Twenty |date= |accessdate=2014-04-19}}</ref>\n* 2008: ''A Road Divided''; Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2008: ''Between the Two'', Yours Gallery, Warsaw, Poland.\n* 2009: ''A Road Divided''; [[Bruce Silverstein Gallery]], New York.\n* 2010: ''Househunting'' / ''Nudes''; Kaune, Sudendorf Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''A Road Divided''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2011: ''Fragmented Narratives''; Bruce Silverstein Gallery, New York.\n* 2012:  ''I Drive...'', La Galerie Particuli\u00e8re, Paris.\n* 2013:  ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''; Kaune, Posnik, Spohr Gallery, Cologne, Germany.\n* 2015: ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey''; Casemore/Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\">https://casemorekirkeby.com/exhibitions/</ref>\n* 2016: ''Intimate Distance''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n* 2019: ''Bright Black World''; Casemore Kirkeby, San Francisco, California<ref name=\"cmke\" />\n\n=== Group ===\n* 2004: ''Light and Atmosphere,'' [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Miami Art Museum]], FL, April 2004 \u2013 January 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pamm.org/exhibitions/light-and-atmosphere | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami]] | title = Light and Atmosphere}}</ref>\n* 2006\u20132007: ''Suburban Escape,'' [[San Jose Museum of Art]], San Jose, CA, September 2006 \u2013 March 2007. Work  by Hido and 29 other photographers.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://sjmusart.org/exhibition/suburban-escape-art-california-sprawl | access-date = 16 June 2016 | publisher = [[San Jose Museum of Art]] | title = Suburban Escape: The Art of California Sprawl}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, March\u2013June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/pier-24-the-inaugural-exhibition/|title=Pier 24: The Inaugural Exhibition \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2010: ''Day & Night,'' Main Exhibition Copenhagen Photo Festival, Copenhagen, Denmark.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-06-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915092646/http://copenhagenphotofestival.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/CPF-PRESS.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-15 }}</ref>\n* 2011\u20132012: ''Here''., [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2011 \u2013 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/here/|title=Here. - Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2012\u20132013: ''About Face'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, May 2012 \u2013 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/about-face/|title=About Face \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2013\u20132014: ''A Sense of Place'', [[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA, July 2013 \u2013 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibition/a-sense-of-place/|title=A Sense of Place \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2016: ''The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip,'' [[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], Bentonville, AR, February\u2013May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crystalbridges.org/the-open-road/|title=The Open Road \u2013 Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|website=crystalbridges.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> Curated by [[David Campany]] and Denise Wolff.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://aperture.org/traveling-exhibitions/open-road/ | access-date = 11 March 2016 | publisher = [[Aperture Foundation]] | title = The Open Road: Photography and the American Road Trip: Curated by David Campany and Denise Wolff}}</ref>\n* 2016\u20132017: ''Collected'', Pier 24 Photography, San Francisco, CA, May 2016 \u2013 January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pier24.org/exhibitions/|title=Exhibitions \u2013 Pier 24|website=Pier24.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1996: Barclay Simpson Award, [[California College of the Arts]], CA. Joinet winner with [[Geoffrey Chadsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/californiacollegeofthearts/docs/barclay25_catalog_lowres|title=Celebrating 25 Years of the Barclay Simpson Award|website=Issuu.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/calendar/2012/barclay-simpson-award-retrospective-exhibition-1987-2012|title=We're All Here Because We're Not All There \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 1998: The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation, Visual Arts Award.<ref group=\"n\">The Wallace Alexander Gerbode Foundation's \"Special Awards Recipients 1987-Present\" PDF [http://foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf here] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908025301/http://www.foundationcenter.org/grantmaker/gerbode/docs/1987-Present-Recipients.pdf |date=2015-09-08 }} does not list Hido.</ref>\n* 1998: Recent Graduate of Distinction Award, California College of the Arts, CA.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n* 2001: Eureka Fellowship, Fleishhacker Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fleishhackerfoundation.org/grants/eureka-fellowship-program/1999-2001/|title=The Fleishhacker Foundation \u2013 1999\u20132001|website=Fleishhackerfoundation.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2002: Best First Monograph of 2001, Photo-Eye.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.photoeye.com/bookstore/citation.cfm?catalog=PK802&i=3902289015&i2=|title=photo-eye Bookstore \u2013 Architecture of Time by Hiroshi Sugimoto \u2013 photobook|website=Photoeye.com|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* 2017: In Focus Artist selected by the National Portrait Gallery UK curators, an annual showcase for new work by an internationally renowned photographer <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/event-root/november/in-conversation-13112017|title=In Conversation: Todd Hido \u2013 National Portrait Gallery|website=Npg.org.uk|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\nHido's work is held in the following public collections:\n{{col-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Art Institute of Chicago]], IL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Hido,+Todd|title=Hido, Todd \u2013 The Art Institute of Chicago|website=Artic.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]], Fort Worth, TX.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartermuseum.org/artworks/779|title=Untitled #2431 \u2013 Todd Hido (b. 1968)|date=6 June 2008|website=Cartermuseum.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive]], Berkeley, CA.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=This Just In: Recent Acquisitions: BAMPFA|url=https://bampfa.org/program/just-recent-acquisitions|website=bampfa.org}}</ref>\n* [[Cleveland Museum of Art]], Cleveland, OH.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandart.org/art/2003.9|title=Untitled #2421 \u2013 Cleveland Museum of Art|website=Clevelandart.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Di rosa]], Napa, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dirosaart.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/Know-the-Rules-_PR.pdf|format=PDF|title=Know the Rules \u2013 Then Break Them Photography from the di Rosa Collection|website=Dirosaart.org\\accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[George Eastman House]], Rochester, NY: 6 prints.<ref>https://collections.eastman.org/people/31393/todd-hido/objects</ref>\n* [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kansas City, MO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kemperart.org/exhibits/CatalogEssays/hidotodd.asp|title=Kemper Museum of Art Exhibitions|publisher=Kemperart.org|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.lacma.org/node/159411|title=Todd Hido \u2013 LACMA Collections|website=collections.lacma.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Madison Museum of Contemporary Art]], Madison, WI.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmoca.org/mmocacollects/artist_page.php?id=13 |title=The MMoCA Collects Site Has Moved |publisher=MMoCA |accessdate=2014-04-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419212451/http://www.mmoca.org/mmocacollects/artist_page.php?id=13 |archivedate=2014-04-19 }}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Contemporary Photography]], Chicago, IL.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Museum of Contemporary Photography|url=http://www.mocp.org/detail.php?t=objects&type=browse&f=maker&s=Hido%252C+Todd&record=0|website=www.mocp.org}}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], MA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.org/collections/object/3235-479742|title=3235|date=3 April 2017|website=Mfa.org|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]], TX.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Untitled #2312-a |url=https://www.mfah.org/art/detail/76295?returnUrl=%252Fart%252Fsearch%253Fartist%253DTodd%252BHido%2526nationality%253DAmerican|website=www.mfah.org}}</ref>\n* [[National Science and Media Museum]], Bradford, UK: 2 prints<ref>https://collection.sciencemuseum.org.uk/people/cp134355/todd-hido</ref>\n* [[New York Public Library]], NY.<ref name=\"nypl\">\"[https://www.nypl.org/sites/default/files/Photographers_in_The_New_York_Public_Library_April_16_2010.pdf Photographers in The New York Public Library's Photography Collection]\". [[New York Public Library]]. Accessed 5 April 2018.</ref>\n* [[North Carolina Museum of Art]], Raleigh, NC.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Search \u2013 Permanent Collection \u2013 NCMA \u2013 North Carolina Museum of Art|url=http://ncartmuseum.org/art/search|website=ncartmuseum.org}}</ref>\n*[[Pier 24 Photography]], San Francisco, CA.<ref>https://pier24.org/collection/</ref>\n* [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]], San Francisco, CA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfmoma.org/artist/Todd_Hido|title=Todd Hido|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], NY.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-04-05|title=Whitney Museum of American Art: Todd Hido: #2663|url=http://collection.whitney.org/object/27261|website=collection.whitney.org}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n== Sources ==\n* [http://www.clevelandart.org/educef/hido/index.aspx Berwick, Carly. Todd Hido: Julie Saul, ART news, November, pp.&nbsp;153\u2013154. 2004.]{{dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb3202/is_200110/ai_n7879833?tag=content;col1: Helfand, Glen. Todd Hido. (Stephen Wirtz), Artforum International, October 2001.]\n* [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0268/is_n9_v36/ai_n27533113/pg_1 Grundberg, Andy. House sitting: the photography of Todd Hido, Artforum, May 1998.]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|www.toddhido.com}}\n* [http://pier24.org/video/todd-hido-house-hunting/ Pier 24 Photography Artist Video: Todd Hido]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131003045644/http://kadist.org/en/people/todd-hido Todd Hido] at [[Kadist Art Foundation]]\n* [http://www.ahornmagazine.com/issue_6/interview_hido/interview_hido.html Interview with Todd Hido \u2013 Ahorn Magazine, Issue 6]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=embdo2Er19A 'Working in the Vicinity of Narrative: Todd Hido and Darius Himes'] from School of Visual Arts. Hido presentation of his career (video)\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hido, Todd}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Photographers from California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:California College of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Ohio]]\n[[Category:People from Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Educators from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Todd Hido\n| image         = Todd Hido by McCall - CC.jpg\n| caption       = Todd Hido, Montana, 2019\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|25}}\n| birth_place   = [[Kent, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[Photography]]\n| education     = [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|B.F.A.]] \u2013 [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] <br/> [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] \u2013 [[California College of the Arts]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        =\n| website       = {{URL|www.toddhido.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Todd Hido''' (born 25 August 1968)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/prc/prcpov/artists/a16.html|title=Todd Hido|website=Bu.edu|accessdate=14 December 2017}}</ref> is an American [[contemporary artist]] and photographer.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-03|title=Todd Hido|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/todd-hido/|website=www.artnet.com}}</ref> He has produced 17 books,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/photography-blog/2013/oct/02/unseen-photo-fair-amsterdam-review|title=A window on weird: step inside the Unseen Photo fair in Amsterdam|first=Sean|last=O'Hagan|date=2 October 2013|accessdate=14 December 2017|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> had his work exhibited widely and included in various public collections.<ref>https://www.mmoca.org/learn/teachers/teaching-pages/todd-hido</ref>\n\n== Life and work ==\nHido was born August 25, 1968, in [[Kent, Ohio]], and graduated from [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Kent, Ohio)|Theodore Roosevelt High School]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |title= Kent City Schools Hall of Fame archives|url=https://www.kentschools.net/hall-of-fame/hall-of-fame-archives/ |year=2009 |work=KentSchools.net |publisher=Kent City School District |accessdate=January 20, 2020}}</ref> He graduated in 1991 with a B.F.A. from [[Tufts University]],<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=December 3, 2018 |title=Todd Hido: Sources and Influences \u2013 Aperture Foundation NY|url=https://aperture.org/workshops-classes/hido-2015/|newspaper=Aperture Foundation NY}}</ref> in [[Medford, Massachusetts]] and [[School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]. Between 1991 and 1992 he studied at [[Rhode Island School of Design]], [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref name=\"hido-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddhido.com/|title=Todd Hido|website=Toddhido.com|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> In 1996 he gained an M.F.A. from [[California College of Arts and Crafts]], [[Oakland, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.edu/academics/graduate/alumni|title=Graduate Alumni \u2013 California College of the Arts|website=Cca.edu|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCurrently based in [[San Francisco]], much of Hido's earlier work involves photographs of urban and suburban housing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://designobserver.com/feature/exposure-suburban-house-at-night-by-todd-hido/39120/|title=Exposure: Surburban house at night, photographed by Todd Hido.|website=Designobserver.com |accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> across the U.S.. He then started to include figures, mostly [[female nude]]s in interiors, and also to depict rural [[landscape]]s. In 2018, he released ''Bright Black World'', his first work photographed outside the U.S. with environmental overtones.\n\nHido says he is influenced by [[Alfred Hitchcock]], [[Edward Hopper]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Robert Adams (photographer)|Robert Adams]], [[Walker Evans]], [[Nan Goldin]], [[Emmet Gowin]], [[Larry Sultan]], [[Alfred Stieglitz]], [[Andreas Gursky]] and [[Rineke Dijkstra]]. Commissioned by Italian brand [[Bottega Veneta]], he photographed actress [[Lauren Hutton]] as well as models [[Joan Smalls]] and [[Vittoria Ceretti]] for the brand's spring/summer 2017 advertisements.<ref>Alexandra Venison (January 16, 2017), [http://www.harpersbazaararabia.com/fashion/the-news/lauren-hutton-stars-in-the-bottega-veneta-springsummer2017-campaign Lauren Hutton Stars In The Bottega Veneta Spring/Summer 2017 Campaign] ''Harper's Bazaar Arabia''.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n=== Publications by Hido ===\n* ''House Hunting''.\n** Portland, OR: [[Nazraeli Press]], 2001. {{ISBN|978-3923922963}}.\n** Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2007. {{ISBN|978-1590051931}}.\n* ''Outskirts''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2002. {{ISBN|978-1590050286}}. Text by [[Luc Sante]]. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Taft Street''. One Picture Book 6. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2001. {{ISBN|978-1590050170}}.\n* ''Roaming''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1590050958}} Edition of 3000 copies.\n* ''Between the Two''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1590051764}}. Edition of 2000 copies.\n* ''Crooked Cracked Tree in Fog''. One Picture Book 60. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-292-1}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Ohio.'' TBW Subscription Series #2. Oakland, CA: TBW, 2009. {{ASIN|B0087G1LD4}}. Edition of 800 copies. The other volumes are by Abner Nolan, Marianne Mueller and [[Alec Soth]].\n* ''A Road Divided''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|978-1590052662}}.\n* ''Nymph Daughters''. Kamakura: Super Labo, 2010. {{ISBN|9784905052012}}. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Excerpts from Silver Meadows''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2013. {{ISBN|978-1590053683}}\n* ''Todd Hido on Landscapes, Interiors, and the Nude.'' The Photography Workshop Series. New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-297-0}}. With an introduction by [[Gregory Halpern]].\n* ''B-Sides \u2013 Silver Meadows.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2014. {{ASIN|B00KP206DO}}. Edition of 500 copies. 50 individual cards in a clear plexi box, similar to a pack of playing cards.\n* ''Khrystyna's World.'' Amsterdam: Reflex Amsterdam, 2015. {{ISBN|978-90-71848-22-3}}. Edition of 500 copies. Published on the occasion of the exhibition, ''Todd Hido: Selections from a Survey: Khrystyna\u2019s World,'' September\u2013November 2015, Reflex Amsterdam, Amsterdam. With an essay by Katya Tylevich, \"Khrystyna's World: Detention in the Getaway Car\".<ref group=\"n\">A PDF of the book can be viewed [http://reflexamsterdam.com/wp-content/themes/newfish/pdf/todd-hido-khrystinas-world.pdf here within the Reflex Gallery website].</ref>\n* ''Seasons Road''. One Picture Book 93. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-456-7}}. Edition of 500 copies. 7 colour plates and 1 photographic print. \"Every year at Christmas for the past ten years, Todd Hido has traveled to Ohio to visit his parents. During his annual trip home, Hido makes photographs along the small road that serves as the namesake for this book.\"<ref>[http://www.nazraeli.com/opb/todd-hido-one-picture-book-93-seasons-road \"Todd Hido | One Picture Book #93 : Seasons Road\"] Nazraeli Press. Accessed 5 October 2016</ref>\n* ''Intimate Distance: Twenty-five Years of Photographs, A Chronological Album.'' New York: Aperture, 2016. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-360-1}}. With an essay by [[David Campany]].\n* ''B-Sides Box Sets \u2013 Homing In.'' Oakland, CA: B-Sides Box Sets, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1-5323-5128-0}}. Edition of 2000 copies. 50 individual cards in a box. Previously unpublished photographs from ''House Hunting.''\n* ''Bright Black World.'' Paso Robles, CA: Nazraeli Press, 2018. {{ISBN|978-1590054758}}. Text by Alexander Nemerov.\n\n=== Smaller publications by Hido ===\n* ''Collage Number Three.'' Deadbeat Club #41. Los Angeles, CA: Deadbeat Club, 2016.  Edition of 500 copies. 8 page zine which folds out to form a poster.\n* ''The Perfect Copy Vol. 1.'' San Francisco, CA: Colpa Press, 2016. Six 4-color [[Risograph]] photographic prints in screen printed envelope. Edition of 100 copies.\n\n=== Publications edited or with contributions by Hido ===\n* ''Witness No. 7''. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052440}}. Photographs by Hido and [[Leon Borensztein]], and photographs of images from books by various people that have inspired Hido.\n* ''Cracked Trees''. One Picture Book 59. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2009. {{ISBN|978-1590052914}}. Photographs by Hido, paintings by 3rd grade students. Edition of 500 copies.\n* ''Motel Club.'' Nazraeli Press Six by Six, set 1 v. 4. Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2010. {{ISBN|1590052978}}. Edition of 100 copies. The other volumes are by [[Anthony Hernandez (photographer)|Anthony Hernandez]], [[Raymond Meeks]], [[Martin Parr]], [[Toshio Shibata]] and [[Mark Steinmetz]].\n* ''Alec Soth's Lonely Boy Mag 2: Boys and Their Cars.'' St. Paul, MN: [[Alec Soth|Little Brown Mushroom]], 2011. Edition of 1000 copies. Text and photographs by Todd Hido, [[Alec Soth]], Chad States and erotic [[diorama]]s by Peter Davidson.\n* ''One Day \u2013 10 Photographers.'' Heidelberg: [[Kehrer Verlag|Kehrer]], 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-86828-173-6}}. A boxed set of ten books of photographs taken on 21 June 2010. Edited by [[Harvey Benge]], each book by one photographer including Todd Hido, Jessica Backhaus, [[Gerry Badger]], Harvey Benge, [[John Gossage]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Rob Hornstra]], [[Rinko Kawauchi]], Eva Maria Ocherbauer and Martin Parr.<ref group=\"n\">The publisher's description of this set: {{Cite web|url=https://www.kehrerverlag.com/en/one-day-10-photographers-978-3-86828-173-6|title=One Day \u2013 Kehrer Verlag|website=Kehrer Verlag|language=en|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n* ''Here.'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2011. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-0-0}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''Leon Borensztein: American Portraits 1979\u20131989.'' Portland, OR: Nazraeli, 2011. {{ISBN|978-1-59005-305-8}}. Photographs by Leon Borensztein. Edited by Hido.\n* ''About Face'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-1-7}}. Exhibition guide\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2013. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-3-1}}. Exhibition guide.\n* ''About Face.'' San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2014. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-2-4}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies. With forewords by Christopher McCall, and [[Richard Avedon]] (from ''In the American West''), an introduction by [[Philip Gefter]], and texts by [[Sandra S. Phillips]], and Ulrike Schneider.\n* ''The Open Road: Photography & the American Road Trip''. Edited and with text by [[David Campany]], photographs by Hido, [[Robert Frank]], [[Ed Ruscha]], [[Inge Morath]], [[Garry Winogrand]], [[William Egglestone]], [[Lee Friedlander]], [[Joel Meyerowitz]], [[Jacob Holdt]], [[Stephen Shore]], [[Bernard Plossu]], [[Victor Burgin]], [[Joel Sternfeld]], [[Shin'ya Fujiwara]], [[Alec Soth]], [[Ryan McGinley]], [[Justine Kurland]], and Taiyo Onorato and Nico Krebs.\n** New York: [[Aperture Foundation|Aperture]], 2014. {{ISBN|978-1-59711-240-6}}.\n** ''Road Trips: Voyages photographiques \u00e0 travers l\u2019Am\u00e9rique.'' Paris: Textuel, 2014. {{ISBN|9782845975002}}. French-language version.\n** ''En la Carretera: Viajes fotogr\u00e1ficos a trav\u00e9s de Norteam\u00e9rica.'' Madrid: La F\u00e1brica, 2014. {{ISBN|9788415691822}}. Spanish-language version.\n* ''A Sense of Place'', San Francisco: Pier 24 Photography, 2015. {{ISBN|978-0-9839917-4-8}}. Exhibition catalog. Edition of 1000 copies.\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n=== Solo ===\n{{BLP sources section|date=December 2018}}\n* 1997: SF Camerawork, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1998: ''House Hunting'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 1999: Inman Gallery, Houston TX.\n* 2000: ''Photographs Taken at Night,'' Kohn Turner Gallery, Los Angeles, CA. Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.\n* 2000: ''Homing In,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2001: ''New Photographs,'' Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX.\n* 2002: The Cleveland Museum of Art, Cleveland, Ohio.\n* 2002: ''Open House,'' Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art.\n* 2002: ''Roaming'', Paul Morris Gallery, New York, NY. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Taft Street, 3A Garage, San Francisco, CA.\n* 2003: Baldwin Gallery, Aspen Colorado. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL.\n* 2004: ''Roaming-New Landscapes'', Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EEDB153BF93BA35753C1A9629C8B63 |author=Glueck, Grace|title=Art in Review : Todd Hido \u2013 'Roaming: New Landscapes'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=October 8, 2004}}</ref>\n* 2004: ''Roaming'', Stephen Wirtz Gallery, San Francisco, CA. Carrie Secrist Gallery, Chicago, IL. Michael Berger Gallery, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. Baldwin Gallery, Aspen, Colorado.\n* 2005 Todd Hido, Sheppard Gallery, University of Nevada, Reno, NV. Inman Gallery, Houston, TX.