:Stet    from:01/10/2008 till:01/05/2009 color:drums\n  bar:Dennis    from:01/05/2009 till:01/10/2010 color:drums\n  bar:Dennis2    from:01/10/2010 till:01/10/2011 color:drums\n  bar:Matt2    from:01/10/2011 till:01/08/2012 color:drums\n  bar:Scott    from:01/08/2012 till:01/03/2014 color:drums\n  bar:Bobby    from:01/03/2014 till:end color:drums\n  bar:David     from:01/01/1986 till:31/12/1993 color:keys\n  bar:Michael     from:01/01/2008 till:01/01/2013 color:keys\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n  color:album\n   at:01/05/1983\n   at:28/05/1984\n   at:02/02/1988\n   at:15/05/1990\n   at:12/11/1991\n   at:14/02/1995\n   at:02/10/2009\n   at:19/06/2012\n}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lita Ford discography}}\n* ''[[Out for Blood (Lita Ford album)|Out for Blood]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Dancin' on the Edge]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Lita (album)|Lita]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Stiletto (album)|Stiletto]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Dangerous Curves (album)|Dangerous Curves]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Black (Lita Ford album)|Black]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Wicked Wonderland (album)|Wicked Wonderland]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Living Like a Runaway]]'' (2012)\n* ''Time Capsule'' (2016)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''Rock 'N Roll Sports Classic''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Highway to Hell_(film)|Highway to Hell]]''\n| The Hitchhiker\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Howie]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Herman's Head]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Edgeplay]]''\n| Herself\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Br\u00fctal Legend]]''\n| Rima\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Big Time Rush]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Lita Ford}}\n* [[List of British Italians]]\n* [[List of Italian-American entertainers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q163211|c=category:Lita Ford|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|q=no|species=no|m=no|mw=no}}\n*{{official website}}\n*{{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/F/Ford%2C_Lita/}}\n*{{IMDb name|0285753}}\n*[https://www.rockerzine.com/2016/07/lita-ford-living-like-runaway-memoir/ \"Lita Ford: Living Like A Runaway, a Memoir\" autobiography book review / Rocker Magazine]\n*[http://www.namm.org/library/oral-history/lita-ford Lita Ford Interview] NAMM Oral History Library (2015/2017)\n\n{{Lita Ford|state=expanded}}\n{{The Runaways}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ford, Lita}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American actresses]]\n[[Category:American female heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American female rock singers]]\n[[Category:American hard rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:English actresses]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:English female guitarists]]\n[[Category:English heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Glam metal musicians]]\n[[Category:English mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:English people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Italian British musicians]]\n[[Category:Lead guitarists]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:The Runaways members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Lita Ford\n| image               = Lita_Ford_at_Jones_Beach_2012_01.jpg\n| caption             = Lita Ford at Jones Beach 2012\n| alt                 = Lita Ford playing a guitar onstage\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Lita Rossana Ford\n| birth_date          = <!-- Please be aware that Lita Ford is not dead - any reports of her death on the internet are hoaxes -->{{birth date and age|df=yes|1958|9|19}}\n| birth_place         = [[London]], England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/lita-ford-17169494|title=Lita Ford Biography|publisher=Biography.com|accessdate=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512204756/http://www.biography.com/people/lita-ford-17169494|archive-date=12 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| origin              = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| instrument          = Guitar, vocals\n| genre               = [[Glam metal]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[punk rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/groups/runaways.htm |title=The Runaways - A Punk Rock History |publisher=Punk77.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-10-31}}</ref>\n| occupation          = Musician, songwriter, singer\n| years_active        = 1975\u20131995, 2008\u2013present\n| label               = [[Mercury Records|Mercury]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], JLRG Entertainment, [[SPV GmbH|SPV/Steamhammer]]\n| associated_acts     = [[The Runaways]], [[Joan Jett]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Cherie Currie]], [[Lemmy]]\n| website             = {{URL|litafordonline.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Lita Rossana Ford''' (born 19 September 1958)<ref>\"Lita Ford.\" ''Contemporary Musicians''. Vol. 9. Detroit: Gale, 1993. Gale Biography In Context. Web. 24 August 2011.</ref><ref>\"Lita Ford.\" ''Almanac of Famous People''. Gale, 2011. Gale Biography In Context. Web. 24 August 2011.</ref> is an English-born, American heavy metal guitarist, actress, vocalist and songwriter who was the lead guitarist for [[the Runaways]] in the late 1970s before embarking on a successful solo career in the 1980s. The 1989 single \"[[Close My Eyes Forever]]\", a duet with [[Ozzy Osbourne]], remains Ford's most successful song, reaching No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"billboard\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/lita-ford|title=Lita Ford|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLita Ford was born to a British father (Harry Lenard Ford) and an Italian mother (Isabella Benvenuto) in London, England.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Living-Like-Runaway-Lita-Ford/dp/0062270648|title=Living Like a Runaway: A Memoir|last=Ford|first=Lita|date=23 February 2016|publisher=Dey Street Books|isbn=9780062270641|edition=First|language=English}}</ref> When she was in second grade, she moved with her family to the United States, eventually settling in [[Long Beach, California]].<ref name=\"podcastone1\">{{cite web|author=Eddie Trunk|url=http://www.podcastone.com/pg/jsp/program/episode.jsp?programID=658&pid=553163|title=ET- Lita Ford \u2013 The Eddie Trunk Podcast|publisher=Podcastone.com|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2012/04/25/lita-ford-runaways|title=Lita Ford on Her Wild Teenage Days in '70s Southern California|last=Ramirez|first=Carlos|date=25 April 2012|work=Noisecreep|publisher=AOL Inc|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nInspired by [[Ritchie Blackmore]]'s work with [[Deep Purple]], she began playing the guitar at the age of 11. Her vocal range is [[mezzo-soprano]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Bill|title=Pro Secrets of Heavy Rock Singing|publisher=Sanctuary Publishing|year=2002|page=9|isbn=1-86074-437-0}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===The Runaways (1975\u20131979)===\nIn 1975, at age 16, Ford was recruited by recording [[impresario]] [[Kim Fowley]] to join the all-female rock band [[The Runaways]]. The band soon secured a recording contract and released their [[The Runaways (album)|first album]] in 1976. The band garnered significant media attention and the Runaways became a successful recording and touring act during their late 1970s heyday. Ford's lead-guitar playing became an integral element of the band's sound until their eventual break-up in April 1979.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lita Ford looks back on The Runaways' breakup: \"We were going in different musical directions\" |url=http://bravewords.com/news/lita-ford-looks-back-on-the-runaways-break-up-we-weren-t-a-team-we-were-going-in-different-musical-directions |website=Brave Words}}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, internal conflicts were erupting within the Runaways, who had by that time already parted ways with producer Fowley, lead singer [[Cherie Currie]], and bassist [[Jackie Fox]]. Vocalist/guitarist [[Joan Jett]] wanted the band to shift to a more [[Ramones]]-influenced [[punk rock|punk rock sound]], while Ford and drummer [[Sandy West]] wanted to continue playing the [[hard rock]]-oriented songs the band had become known for.<ref name=\"Sherman, Dale p53\">Sherman, Dale. ''20th Century Rock And Roll: Women In Rock''. Collector's Guide Publishing, Inc, p53</ref> With neither faction willing to compromise, the band finally broke up in April 1979.<ref name=\"Sherman, Dale p53\"/>\n\n===Solo career (1980\u20131995)===\n[[File:Lita Ford by Zoran Veselinovic.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Ford performing on 19 December 1988 in the \"Olympiahalle\" venue of [[Munich]], Germany.]]\nFollowing the breakup of the Runaways, Ford signed with [[Mercury Records]] and set about launching a solo career. Her debut solo album, entitled ''[[Out for Blood (Lita Ford album)|Out for Blood]]'', was released in 1983 and was a commercial disappointment. Her next release, ''[[Dancin' on the Edge]]'' (1984) achieved moderate success and Ford's popularity began to rise. ''Dancin' on the Edge'' included the single \"Fire in My Heart\", which reached the Top 10 in several countries outside the United States. The follow-up single, \"Gotta Let Go\", performed better, reaching number one on the Mainstream Rock charts. Ford said in an interview that she recorded an unreleased album with [[RCA Records]], and [[Tony Iommi]] didn't perform on it.<ref name=\"podcastone1\"/>\n\nFord signed with [[RCA Records]], hired [[Sharon Osbourne Management]], and re-emerged with a more radio-friendly [[Glam metal|pop-metal]] sound. In 1988, she released her most commercially successful album, the self-produced ''[[Lita (album)|Lita]]''. The album featured several singles including \"[[Kiss Me Deadly (song)|Kiss Me Deadly]]\", \"Back to the Cave\", \"[[Close My Eyes Forever]]\", and \"Falling in and Out of Love\", a song co-written by [[Nikki Sixx]] of [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]]. The ballad \"Close My Eyes Forever\", a duet with [[Ozzy Osbourne]], remains her most successful song, reaching No. 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"billboard\" />\nFord followed up the success of ''Lita'' with the album ''[[Stiletto (album)|Stiletto]]'' (1990). ''Stiletto'' featured the singles \"Hungry\" and \"Lisa\" (a song dedicated to her mother). However, the album failed to match the success of her previous release. Ford's next release was ''[[Dangerous Curves (album)|Dangerous Curves]]'' (1991), which featured her last charting single to date, \"Shot of Poison\". Ford's final album prior to a lengthy recording hiatus was ''[[Black (Lita Ford album)|Black]]'' on the German [[ZYX Records]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Long hiatus (1996\u20132007)===\n[[File:Lita Ford.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Ford performing on 27 June 2009.]]\nBy the mid-1990s, Ford placed a reduced priority on her music career as she turned her attention towards raising her two young sons. Following the release of ''Black'' in 1995, Ford did not release new material until the ''[[Wicked Wonderland (album)|Wicked Wonderland]]'' album in 2009.\n\n===Return to stage (2008\u2013present)===\nIn June 2008, Ford re-emerged with a new band with Stet Howland (WASP) on drums, playing several warm-up gigs under the moniker ''Kiss Me Deadly'' prior to [[Rocklahoma]] in Pryor, Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eddietrunk.com/index.cfm/pk/view/cd/NAA/cdid/402306/pid/401816|title=Eddie Trunk|publisher=EddieTrunk.com|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927224552/http://www.eddietrunk.com/index.cfm/pk/view/cd/NAA/cdid/402306/pid/401816|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2009, she toured the United States and Europe with a new line-up on her last 14 shows consisting of former [[Guns N' Roses]] guitarist [[Bumblefoot (musician)|Ron 'Bumblefoot' Thal]], drummer [[Dennis Leeflang]], and [[Deepfield (band)|Deepfield]] bassist PJ Farley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/guns-n-roses-guitarist-bumblefoot-to-tour-with-lita-ford|title=Guns N' Roses Guitarist Bumblefoot To Tour With Lita Ford|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandsintown.com/LitaFord/past_events?page=5|title=Lita Ford Tour History from 2008 to 2016: Lita Ford Past Tour Dates|publisher=Bandsintown.com|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long recording hiatus, Ford released the new album ''[[Wicked Wonderland (album)|Wicked Wonderland]]'' on 6 October 2009, on the JLRG Entertainment label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.live-metal.net/interviews_litaford.html|title=Lita Ford: The Next Chapter In Her Rockin' History|accessdate=14 March 2010|last=Price|first=Jason|date=12 November 2008|publisher=Live-Metal.net}}</ref> In an interview with ExclusiveMagazine.com, Ford spoke about her new material: \"I just wanted to kick ass! I don't know what's popular, or the flavor of the day. I just wanted the music to rock! The lyrics are very personal and that's it. I wasn't going to come out in sandals with hairy armpits!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annecarlini.com/ex_interviews.php?id=1017|work=Exclusive Magazine|accessdate=5 September 2010|author=Russell A. Trunk|title=''Desert Island Diva!''}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Ford promised to release a \"real comeback album\" later in the year with drummer Chuck Spradlin, saying that 2009's [[nu metal]]-inspired ''Wicked Wonderland'', was too much of a collective project with ex-husband [[Jim Gillette]]. \"A lot of people have told me that they want a real Lita Ford album, and I know what they mean. They are going to get it\", she was quoted as saying at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=158264|title=Lita Ford: New Video Interview Posted Online|publisher=Roadrunnerrecords.com|accessdate=28 December 2012}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe album ''[[Living Like a Runaway]]'' was released in June 2012 on [[SPV GmbH|SPV/Steamhammer Records]]. True to her word, the album was much more in line with her earlier work. The title is also celebratory, as Ford had recently settled differences with her former Runaways' bandmates.<ref>{{cite web|author=Greg Prato|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/album-premiere-lita-ford-living-like-a-runaway-20120618|title=Album Premiere: Lita Ford, 'Living Like a Runaway'|work=Rolling Stone|date=18 June 2012|accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref> During 2014 she was bestowed with The Certified Legend Award by [[Guitar Player Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guitarplayer.com/players/the-2014-guitar-player-hall-of-fame-awards|title=The 2014 Guitar Player Hall of Fame Awards|date=17 November 2014|publisher=guitarplayer.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Ford released the album ''Time Capsule'' \u2013 a collection of songs she discovered on old analogue tapes from the 80s featuring recordings she'd made with [[Billy Sheehan]], [[Gene Simmons]], [[Bruce Kulick]], [[Robin Zander]], [[Rick Nielsen]], [[Dave Navarro]], Rodger Carter and [[Jeff Scott Soto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/lita-ford-is-bringing-back-the-80s-with-time-capsule|title=Lita Ford Is Bringing Back The '80s with 'Time Capsule'|publisher=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn the mid-1980s, Ford was briefly engaged to guitarist [[Tony Iommi]] of [[Black Sabbath]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Tony Iommi profile |publisher=Internet Movie Database |url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0409546/bio|accessdate=26 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lita Ford History: Sleaze Roxx |url=http://www.sleazeroxx.com/bands/fordlita/litaford.shtml |accessdate=26 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812234644/http://www.sleazeroxx.com/bands/fordlita/litaford.shtml |archivedate=12 August 2011 }}</ref> Iommi co-produced her album ''The Bride Wore Black'', which was never released. Ford said in a 1989 interview with [[Kerrang!]] magazine that \"there's a certain amount of bad blood between Tony and I\".\n\nFord was married to [[W.A.S.P. (band)|W.A.S.P.]] guitarist [[Chris Holmes (musician)|Chris Holmes]] in the early 1990s for a short time. After the couple divorced, Ford met former [[Nitro (band)|Nitro]] vocalist [[Jim Gillette]] in 1994 and the couple were married after knowing each other for only two weeks. They have two sons, James and Rocco Gillette. The family moved to [[Turks and Caicos]], where Gillette operated a small building and real estate developing business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outpostmagazine.com/tanyourmind/story.php?title=colonies-and-territories&user=ryan|title=Colonies and Territories|publisher=Outpostmagazine.com|date=20 March 2009|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823220639/http://outpostmagazine.com/tanyourmind/story.php?title=colonies-and-territories&user=ryan|archivedate=23 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe marriage to Gillette began to crumble after he entered into negotiations with [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]] for a [[Reality television|reality TV show]], tentatively titled ''The Gillettes: An Extreme American Family''. In a March 2011 interview on the Classic Rock Revisited website, Ford claimed that she had taken a business trip to Los Angeles to discuss the show with TLC executives, and returned home to find her husband and sons not speaking to her.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Jeb|title=Nightmares & Dreams both Come True: An interview with Lita Ford|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015184203/http://classicrockrevisited.com/interviewLitaFord.htm|website=Classic Rock Revisited|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> Ford claimed that Gillette turned the couple's children against her, claiming that she was going to do harm to them, after she had assumed a greater level of control in the proposed series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/lita-ford-wikipedia-fact-or-fiction-runaways-family-more|title=Lita Ford Plays Wikipedia: Fact or Fiction?|publisher=Loudwire.com|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref> Ford subsequently claimed that Gillette began encouraging her sons to physically attack her, a situation which prompted her to seek a divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicrockrevisited.com/interviewLitaFord.htm|title=Lita Ford interview|publisher=Classicrockrevisited.com|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015184203/http://classicrockrevisited.com/interviewLitaFord.htm|archivedate=15 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a February 2011 radio interview, Ford acknowledged that her marriage to Gillette was indeed over,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/soundcheck/lita_ford_ugly_divorce_inspired_new_albums_lyrics.html|title=Lita Ford interview|publisher=Ultimate-guitar.com|date=26 January 2011|accessdate=9 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205085034/http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/news/soundcheck/lita_ford_ugly_divorce_inspired_new_albums_lyrics.html|archivedate=5 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ending any plans for a television series. Following the end of her relationship with Gillette, Ford became an advocate for the awareness of [[parental alienation]].\n\nIn 2016 Ford published her autobiography, ''Living Like a Runaway: A Memoir'', through Dey Street Books. In the book, Ford claimed that she quit The Runaways in 1979 after coming to the conclusion that her bandmates \"were all gay\", a situation she didn't feel comfortable with. She wrote that she found it \"strange\" that they never spoke about boys with her and were \"always giggling about other girls\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/lita-ford-left-the-runaways-after-learning-about-gay-bandmates_n_56ce07d9e4b041136f193847|title=Lita Ford Reveals She Quit The Runaways Because Her Bandmates 'Were All Gay'|first=Kira|last=Brekke|date=29 February 2016|website=HuffPost.com|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Acting and other projects==\n[[File:Lita Ford and Patrick Kennison.jpg|thumb|Ford performing with [[Patrick Kennison]]]]\nDuring her solo career, Ford endorsed musical instrument manufacturer [[B.C. Rich]] and exclusively used several of the brand's guitars, most notably [[B.C. Rich Warlock|the Warlock]]. The 1992 TV series ''[[Howie (TV series)|Howie]]'', starring [[Howie Mandel]], saw Ford as a regular guitarist for the house band. Ford also had a small role in the 1992 horror/comedy film ''[[Highway to Hell (film)|Highway to Hell]]'' playing a character called \"The Hitchhiker\". Ford was also asked by [[VH-1]] to join the cast of the seventh season of the reality television program ''[[The Surreal Life]]'' in 2007, to which she declined.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lita Ford 'Turned Down' Chance to Appear in 'Surreal Life' |url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/lita-ford-turned-down-chance-to-appear-in-the-surreal-life/ |website=Blabbermouth.net}}</ref>\nFord contributed her likeness and voice to the [[Xbox 360]], [[PlayStation 3]] and PC video game ''[[Br\u00fctal Legend]]''. She appears as the character Rima, alongside [[Jack Black]], [[Tim Curry]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Rob Halford]] and [[Lemmy Kilmister]]. Her song \"Betrayal\" is also one of the 100+ songs that appear in the game.\n\nIn 2010, a major Hollywood motion picture chronicling the career of Ford's first band, The Runaways, was produced. Ford was portrayed by actress [[Scout Taylor-Compton]] in the movie, entitled ''[[The Runaways (2010 film)|The Runaways]]''. Ford is featured extensively in the 2005 documentary film ''[[Edgeplay: A Film About the Runaways]]'', in which she spoke candidly about her time in the all-female band. Among other things, she alludes to verbal and sexual abuse endured by the band members at the hands of their management, specifically Kim Fowley.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\nIn 2013, Ford reunited with former [[The Runaways|Runaways]] bandmate [[Cherie Currie]] to record a Christmas single.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/aug/27/runaways-lita-ford-cherie-currie-reunite-christmas Lita Ford & Cherie Currie \u2013 2013 Christmas single], ''The Guardian'', 27 August 2013.</ref> The single ties into work Currie and Ford are both doing on behalf of [[Toys for Tots]], a charity run by the US Marine Corps, which gives holiday toys to children of need.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rock pioneer Lita Ford to shred at Naperville's Last Fling |url=https://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150901/entlife/150909921/ |website=Daily Herald}}</ref>\n\nFord appeared on the May/June 2013 cover of ''[[Making Music Magazine]]'' to discuss her life and career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://makingmusicmag.com/rock-and-roll-moms|title=Lita Ford: Rock and Roll Moms|date=1 May 2013|accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Ford narrated ''The Life, Blood, and Rhythm of [[Randy Castillo]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt4384478/|title=The Life, Blood and Rhythm of Randy Castillo|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFord competed on the reality cook show ''[[Chopped (TV series)|Chopped]]'' in hopes of raising $10,000 for her charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/shows/chopped/2400-series/rock-stars.html|title=Rock Stars: Chopped|publisher=Food Network|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref> Ford made it through the first round, but was eliminated in the second round.\n\nFord released her autobiography ''Living Like a Runaway'' in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.harpercollins.com/9780062270641/living-like-a-runaway|title=Living Like a Runaway \u2013 Lita Ford \u2013 Hardcover|first=Lita|last=Ford|website=HarperCollins US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lita Ford and Jim Cara started Lita Ford Guitars, creating guitars and experiences for fans and players.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.axs.com/interview-lita-ford-talks-new-tour-music-and-career-highlights-129325|title=Interview: Lita Ford talks new tour, music and career highlights|work=AXS|access-date=2019-03-27|language=en-US}}</ref>{{#tag:timeline|\nImagesize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:18\nPlotArea = left:120 bottom:90 top:10 right:20\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1982 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n   id:vocals      value:red        legend:Lead_Vocals\n   id:guitar      value:green      legend:Guitars\n   id:bass        value:blue       legend:Bass\n   id:drums       value:orange     legend:Drums\n   id:keys         value:purple     legend:Keyboards\n   id:album       value:black      legend:Studio_Album\n\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:2 start:1982\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:1982\n\nBarData =\n   bar:Lita   text:\"Lita Ford\"\n   bar:Mitch       text:\"Mitch Perry\"\n   bar:Patrick     text:\"Patrick Kennison\"\n   bar:Neil   text:\"Neil Merryweather\"\n   bar:Hugh  text:\"Hugh McDonald\"\n   bar:Don          text:\"Don Nossov\"\n   bar:Matt   text:\"Matt Bissonette\"\n   bar:Larry       text:\"Larry Dennison\"\n   bar:Greg   text:\"Greg Hampton\"\n